text:
@standard.gentlemen
. . .
my social media feeds filled with hatred this week. some calling a woman a liar for not reporting abuse earlier. some demanding that i be enraged, take a stand for women, and go after those accused of sexual abuse. no...both sides are innocent until proven otherwise.
i have loved women that were victims of rape and sexual abuse. i have seen the tremendous affect it had on their lives...how it impacted our relationships. one had only told a few friends. none told the police. i believed them and supported them as best i knew how at that time. my business was created to help men grow and evolve to lead with purpose, integrity, and respect for others...especially women. a woman‚Äôs body belongs to her and no one has a right to lay a hand on her without permission. i will always stand with women claiming abuse, but i won‚Äôt pass judgment without knowledge of direct facts. social media posts are not direct facts.
on the other side, i‚Äôve been falsely accused of sexual abuse. i was vilified and labeled as guilty due to my former wife‚Äôs claims that i physically abused her and sexually abused our daughter. i had my entire world ripped out from under me. they didn‚Äôt have to prove guilt. i had to prove my innocence. how do you prove that nothing happened? where is that evidence? even with no evidence, including a physical examination of my daughter and her denial, it has been a massive mountain i have climbed over and over. i continuously countered these claims with clear and documented facts that exposed them as false. i divorced her, received control of our house and property, pay zero alimony, and she was ordered to pay $83,000 in attorney fees to me. i was later granted sole custody of our daughter. let that sink in.
she then took the same claims to another court, and with all the facts, history, and documents in front of them, i was again labeled guilty until proven innocent. my daughter was taken from me. lives were destroyed and a little girl‚Äôs life ripped apart. that is the real abuse. i will also stand with the accused until i become aware of direct facts to support otherwise.
my emotions don‚Äôt dictate my decisions.
seek the truth.

text:
trying to do some knitting to not think about what is going on in the country right now. 
i'm felling so. angry, sad, terrible, vulnerable. social media doesn't seem like the right format to talk about it. but since social media is such an important form of communication today,  as an artist i can ignore what is happening.

i find myself surprised how many times i've accepted things that i shouldn't have because i didn't feel like i had a choice. i hope this conversion will create change. i suppose had told myself sexist men were the exception but after last week it's feeling more like this is the normal. 
#cancelkavanaugh
#timesup
#metoo #women #art #love #webelievesurvivors #heart #knit #knittersofinstagram #yarnlover #yarn #knittingastherapy #knitting #crochet #crochetersofinstagram

text: this day is one of my first memories. i was probably 3? 4? i remember being topless at glamour shots and being wrapped up with a feather boa. i was so uncomfortable, i felt wrong, i didn‚Äôt like that part. i started to throw a fit. my parents begged me to take one more photo ‚Äúfor your cousin lauren, for your cousin jennifer‚Äù i remember them trying to bribe me. i was a baby. and i don‚Äôt blame my parents but the stress and trauma of being a baby and being naked and covered in makeup and hairspray and surrounded by strangers with cameras has stuck with me my entire life. i‚Äôve never had a healthy relationship with sexuality - the sexuality of others, my own sexuality, the concept of sexuality in general. i‚Äôve been viewed and treated as a sexual object literally since i can remember and this has created a totally morphed and sick idea of what sexuality is and the role it should play in your life. i‚Äôve had too many inappropriate interactions to even count beginning around age 9. i‚Äôve been sexually assaulted and raped multiple times, when i was 16 i dated a guy i was totally infatuated with who hit me when we had sex. i had just recently lost my virginity and didn‚Äôt know if it was normal or not so i let him hit me. i‚Äôve been raped by boyfriends while we were fighting. i‚Äôve been raped by strangers, i‚Äôve been raped by friends who i trusted enough to get drunk around. i‚Äôve loved and stayed with multiple partners who tried to impregnate me against my will, one of whom was successful. and most of the time i‚Äôve made excuses and blamed myself for these experiences. yes, a self-proclaimed feminist blamed herself and excused her abusers and held this all inside until it tore me up, literally and figuratively. there is no doubt in my mind that these health issues i‚Äôm having directly correlate to the pain and abuse i‚Äôve harbored in my female parts. nor do i doubt that my symptoms are worsening in part due to the emotional stress and terror that women are living through right now in the u.s. so yeah, i believe dr. christine blasey ford, i believe all women. and i understand why women don‚Äôt come forward because never once did i come forward, i was too scared (cont. in comments)

text:
this past week has been extremely emotionally draining. it is a triggering time for survivors of sexual assault and abuse, and discouraging for victims (present and future). as a researcher of sexual assault victimization and perpetration, i‚Äôm exhausted, but trying to stay hopeful. i struggle with how to communicate my thoughts about this topic on social media and with the public because it‚Äôs a lot of pressure, makes me vulnerable, and it isn‚Äôt an easy topic to talk about - but at the same time i feel a sense of obligation, like its my duty to say something. and i have a lot to say. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
one message that resonated through the conference on campus sexual assault that i want to leave you with is how important it is to believe victims. as few as 1 in 5 victims actually report their sexual assault, so they don‚Äôt get the health they need. victims are more likely to tell someone close to them about the assault than legal authorities. it is important to consider how we treat victims who come forward. if victims feel judged, blamed, shamed, or treated like they are lying, making it up, or not remembering correctly, victims can undergo ‚Äúsecondary victimization‚Äù through which they are traumatized by the social reactions they receive in response to disclosing theirs sexual assault, on top of the trauma they are bearing from the victimization. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
what can you do?
when someone discloses that they have been sexually assaulted or abused, avoid asking ‚Äúwhy‚Äù questions because they can come off as accusatory and make survivors blame themselves. instead: 1) listen to them, 2) assure them you believe them, 3) be supportive and 4) ask how you can help. #startbybelieving
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
for more information and resources to get help, visit the link in my bio. and as always - i‚Äôm here to talk ‚ù§Ô∏è show your support to the survivors out there, many who have kept their victimization to themselves, and let them know you believe them by commenting #ibelievesurvivors ‚¨áÔ∏è

text: going out for a run. i stretch to protect from injury. i wear shoes to protect my feet. i wear reflective clothing and blinking light so cars can see me. i keep my music off so i can be more aware of my surroundings. and i carry this to protect myself from a potential male attacker. i‚Äôve never had to use it before and i hope i never have to. but it‚Äôs there because there have been some close calls. cars that lingered just a little too long at the stop sign waiting for me to approach. guys on bikes or on foot that ‚Äúcoincidentally‚Äù end up on multiple points on my route even though i passed them 15 minutes ago. cat calls. long stares. giggling. i get angry when i think about it. angry to the point of tears. i consider myself strong, brave, fierce. but helpless to the unwanted advances and threats of men. ugh. #knowbetter #dobetter #metoo #fighter #notavictim #teachboystorespectgirls

text:
when people say..
.
"you didn't try and fight him off? the rape/sexual assault is your own fault."
.
let's get one thing straight..
.
if you are going to put your dick inside of a person, it's your job to make absolute sure you have the consent of the person.
it's your job to make sure they are awake enough and sober enough to consent.
.
get a clear "yes".
.
in a relationship, create clear guidelines on what you both are okay with, because yes it is possible to rape your significant other
.
another thing..
.
it's easy to assume how you would handle a sexual assault when you've never experienced one.
.
yeah it's easy to assume you'd immediately go into ass kicking mode. but you really don't actually know
.
sometimes people have the reaction of fight, sometimes they flight, sometimes they freeze.
.
sometimes you try to enforce a boundary that someone keeps pushing and you convince yourself you were okay with it because it feels easier to lie to yourself and comply than face the truth and trauma of what you actually experienced
.
sometimes you are in shock, sometimes it's feels complicated because it happens with someone you trusted. sometimes it feels complicated because you consented up to a certain extent
.
your unconscious survival drives kick in during a trauma to keep you alive which isn't always.... "i kicked his ass."
.
you either consented or you didn't. plain and simple.
.
whether you tried to fight off the person that assaulted you, whether you froze, whether you convinced yourself to go along with it, i fucking believe you and your feelings are valid.
.
if you've never experienced a sexual assault you should probably stop telling other people how they should have handled it.
.
i have talked to many women this week and have heard many horror stories around their sexuality and also had many men reach out to me to ask me to further clarify what consensual sex looks like. (hallelujah)
.
one thing i know for sure is... even though i personally believe there are a bunch of ignorant people giving terrible input on this subject this is a topic we all need to keep talking about because clearly a lot of people need sexual healing and empowerment.

text:
just as i believe anita hill, i believe dr. christine blasey ford.
üí´
i have been sexually assaulted more than once. the first time i had sex, i didn‚Äôt want to have sex. a friend of mine was raped and sexually assaulted throughout high school and is called a slut for it to this day.
üí´
i've had both men and women dismiss these statements. and i‚Äôve also had them acknowledge and discuss these experiences with me. this post does not exist to highlight the facts we already know: most men don‚Äôt believe women when they share their story. this posts exists to call out the women in the room: why aren‚Äôt you believing your sisters? how are we allowing their truth to make us uncomfortable to the point of disbelief?
üí´
the following are two statements from women regarding dr. ford‚Äôs testimony. we already know most men are at this level. but our own kind?
üí´
‚Äúwhy do i have to believe dr. ford because i‚Äôm a woman? there are too many holes in her story.‚Äù
üí´
‚Äúford may have been sexually abused. i do not believe it was kavanaugh. this is wrong to ruin a good man's reputation. i heard she got around in high school...‚Äù
üí´
what????? why do women do this to eachother?? ü§Æ
üí´
songs have played on this double-standard for as long as i remember.
üí´
christina aguilera‚Äôs ‚Äúwon‚Äôt hold us down‚Äù is just one example: ‚Äúif you look back in history it's a common double standard of society. the guy gets all the glory the more he can score, while the girl can do the same yet you call her a whore. i don't understand why it's ok, the guy can get away with it, the girl gets named.‚Äù
üí´
and the list goes on....
üí´
i‚Äôve always had mixed emotions about women and i have wanted to talk about this for a long time. but alas, i‚Äôve kept my mouth shut due to fear of backlash... from women. ironic, isn‚Äôt it? but these comments have sparked enough strength for me to get into it.
üí´
the #womensupportingwomen movement is one that‚Äôs important to me, but it's discouraging to see a withdrawl of support. give your head a shake. we need you.
üí´
i want to say more. i haven't always been a good woman to my kind. but we can be better. first the pain, then the rising. ‚ù§
üí´
#believewomen #believesurvivors #fuckyoukavanaugh

text:
these last couple weeks have been so draining, so infuriating (to put it mildly). i hope everyone is finding ways to take care. @carolinecatlin and i channeled our outrage into a new project‚Äîyouarenotontrial.com. we are working to create a space that supports survivors and empowers the pain and frustration and anger that so many of us (survivors, allies, advocates) are feeling.
.

youarenotontrial.com is a place to hear and share voice memos of support, of validation. and it is a place for survivors to find resources, for anyone to find resources to support survivors, and for anyone to find ways to engage politically.
.
.
thank you to everyone who is standing up, thank you to everyone fighting. even if this fight is not public, even if this fight is not shared: i believe you, i hear you, i support you. .
.

check out the site and engage with what you are drawn to! we‚Äôd love your voices, we‚Äôd love your feedback (questions, comments, critique, etc), we‚Äôd love your help in making this a responsible, supportive site.
.

find the website link in my bio, and please share the site (publicly, privately) if you know anyone who would appreciate it ‚ù§Ô∏è
.
also, i‚Äôve been getting some requests for prints of this drawing! if that is something you are interested in please message me directly or contact through the website. they will be used to fundraise for rainn.

text:
i wouldn‚Äôt have been about to report my first sexual assault even if i wanted to because i had no idea who assaulted me. .
it happened when i was unconscious, and i only woke up for just enough time to know what was happening. it was at a house party during summer after freshman year of college, and i was likely the drunkest i‚Äôve ever been. i only remember little blurbs of that evening, and i have no memory of how i got that intoxicated. .
in the morning i told a friend who was there what had happened. and i so badly needed to get out of there that i drove home still drunk. .
not long after getting home i remember asking my dad if he would make me chicken noodle soup. he said no because i did this to myself. granted he was speaking of the hangover, but how powerful are those words? ‚Äúyou did this to yourself.‚Äù and then a friend stopped by and let me know that the girl i told had been mocking me about what said happened. i was so hurt. not only did i do this to myself, but i was also on my own to deal with it. .
had i known who did it i wouldn‚Äôt have reported it. it had already been traumatizing enough. i was also terrified of seeing the people i knew who were at that party, and i can‚Äôt even say i know why. about 5 years later the friend who mocked me apologized even though we had never discussed it. i accepted the apology, but the hard lesson about the fallout of talking about sexual assault had already been learned. .
this week has been hard. i‚Äôm angry. and i‚Äôm even angrier knowing that there are likely people in my life who support kavanaugh and are unable to even hear dr. ford‚Äôs pain. i don‚Äôt know how to leave this other than saying that we‚Äôve really got to do better. .
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
...believe survivors! ‚ú®
wow. last week was filled with so many different things. i stayed quiet just to take everything in. saw so many different sides of the proverbial fence that people sat on. and i also saw some stay silent. it‚Äôs rough + icky when these types of muddy waters lurk in, i guess. it‚Äôs easy + comfortable to be impartial. but we live in a time where your voice must be heard. go vote, make a difference, and eff sh*t up in the best way!
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
i have no lengthy words concerning our patriarchal-government that hasn‚Äôt already been said. i just wanna extend a warm virtual hug to anyone that has been triggered in some way by recent events. anyone that has had to relive their own trauma, be it past or present. anyone that feels like no one helped them, listened to them, saw them, or questioned them. if you need someone to talk to, please feel free to dm me anytime.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
also, friends, please be mindful when using the binary (male/female) when talking about sexual assault. it is not gender specific. i realize that most are referring to recent events however assault is assault regardless of how one may identify themselves. please be kind to others, you never know what someone is going through üñ§üí´

i will not "go dark" or slither into a corner to hide or sit down and be quiet.

i will take up space.

i will continue to speak. about trauma. about how our racist, misogynist, patriarchal culture is traumatizing. about how we need to end rape culture.  about how the "boys club" needs to be burned down to the ground.

i will continue to do my work with sexual trauma survivors. with intimate partner violence survivors. with survivors of childhood abuse, neglect, and harm.

i will continue to believe survivors and to use my voice to tell them so.

i will stand in solidarity with persons of color and fight racism and especially gendered racism and use my privilege to the liberation of all of us. 
i will continue to do my inner work of taking off the leash that was put on me by our culture. and i will continue to talk about it.

today. tomorrow. and all my days to come.

#allmyselfiesarefeministselfies #iveneverbeengoodatbeingquiet #timesupnow #timesup #metoo #believesurvivors #ibelievechristineblaseyford #endrapeculture #growconsentculture #riseup #becomingunleashed

text:
re-share: men ask why women are so pissed off. even guys with wives and daughters. jackson katz, a prominent social researcher, illustrates why.  he's done it with hundreds of audiences: "i draw a line down the middle of a chalkboard, sketching a male symbol on one side and a female symbol on the other.
then i ask just the men: what steps do you guys take, on a daily basis, to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? at first there is a kind of awkward silence as the men try to figure out if they've been asked a trick question. the silence gives way to a smattering of nervous laughter. occasionally, a young a guy will raise his hand and say, 'i stay out of prison.' this is typically followed by another moment of laughter, before someone finally raises his hand and soberly states, 'nothing. i don't think about it.'
then i ask the women the same question. what steps do you take on a daily basis to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? women throughout the audience immediately start raising their hands. as the men sit in stunned silence, the women recount safety precautions they take as part of their daily routine.
hold my keys as a potential weapon. look in the back seat of the car before getting in. carry a cell phone. don't go jogging at night. lock all the windows when i sleep, even on hot summer nights. be careful not to drink too much. don't put my drink down and come back to it; make sure i see it being poured. own a big dog. carry mace or pepper spray. have an unlisted phone number. have a man's voice on my answering machine. park in well-lit areas. don't use parking garages. don't get on elevators with only one man, or with a group of men. vary my route home from work. watch what i wear. don't use highway rest areas. use a home alarm system. don't wear headphones when jogging. avoid forests or wooded areas, even in the daytime. don't take a first-floor apartment. go out in groups. own a firearm. meet men on first dates in public places. make sure to have a car or cab fare. don't make eye contact with men on the street. make assertive eye contact with men on the street.‚Äù ‚Äï jackson katz
name: Heidi McIvor Allen

text:
this bullshit excuse of ‚Äúwhy didn‚Äôt you report your sexual assault sooner‚Äù needs to disappear immediately. -

trigger warning: sexual assault. -

i had an old massage job where the owner refused to be massaged by anyone but me. i shrugged it off initially, we all have our favorite massage therapist ‚Äî i know i do. during our intake interviews, he would find reasons to ‚Äúinnocently‚Äù touch my arm, my lower back, my neck. at times during the massage he would squirm to try and touch my arm or my hand when i was working on his upper body. i got a sick feeling in my gut, but i once again, shrugged it off (because as women, this is often how we are conditioned to cope with aggressive behavior). until one day, he touched himself repeatedly under the sheets ‚Äî over and over for about 40 minutes. i started silently crying and panicked: this was a power move. he could easily fire me. it would be his word, the owner, against mine. i finished the massage, ran to the back room, and bawled. i grabbed my phone and texted aris and a close guy friend. my guy friend responded first. in response to my panicked text i received: ‚Äúhahaha oh god men are gross. how funny though! what a compliment. you must be great at massage.‚Äù i collected myself and returned to the front room to close out the massage session. with a grin and a wink, he handed me a $20 cash tip. the next day i told my manager. ‚Äúoh. huh. well....i heard he‚Äôs having some marital issues. maybe that‚Äôs why that happened?‚Äù then nothing happened. i quickly left that job and got an amazing job with incredible women. i think my old job made the owner sign some misconduct paperwork, but i can‚Äôt be 100% sure. in any case, no one followed up with me. -

here are some huge issues with this situation: 1) if you‚Äôre thinking about sexually assaulting someone: don‚Äôt do it, you human garbage. 2) if someone tells you about a time they were assaulted: don‚Äôt laugh about it and make jokes. 3) if you‚Äôre in a position of power to help someone: help them and don‚Äôt make poor excuses for shitty behavior. -

i told my manager about my assault the next day and no one fucking cared. so, someone please tell me: when is ‚Äúthe right time‚Äù to report?

text:
‚Äúboys will be boys‚Äù has always troubled me because the words carefully entrap males into believing that they have to behave in a certain manner to be seen as ‚Äúmen‚Äù. this statement only serves as an excuse, welcoming intolerable and untoward sexual behavior towards another. it is untrue for myself, it is untrue for my father, it is untrue for my brothers, and it is untrue for many men. this statement only propagates the untruth that what it is to be a ‚Äúman‚Äù is directly tied to sexual conquest. moreover, it foments self-doubt into the minds of young males, begging the question of what behavior launches us into manhood. this i know to be true. the truth is, not engaging in the ‚Äúboys will be boys‚Äù behavior does not make you non-masculine, too sensitive or homosexual, it makes you respectful and decent. and that is alright.

men, it is important for us to break with the status quo, speak out on behalf of and with women, showing the world that this is what being a man indeed is. #metoo #boyswillbeboys #boyswontbeboys #manhood #masculine #boys #behavior #education #knowledge #wisdom #timesup #inspiration #change #equality #sexualassault #sexualviolence #motivation #wordsofwisdom #mystory #man #respect #love #sensitive

‚Å£
i know i‚Äôm not alone, and that devastates me. it feels so unfair. it is unfair.‚Å£

text: you guys. this tattoo, the one on my arm. it says: ‚Äúyou save yourself or remain unsaved.‚Äù it‚Äôs about the hell i put myself through and the climbing back out of it. if you‚Äôve followed me for a while, you already know it all. i gotta tell you though. this weekend. y‚Äôall have shown me that although, yes, it is ultimately on me. other people can help you save yourself in ways you didn‚Äôt even know. to every person who sent me a message asking if i was ok ‚Äî even when, and especially when, they were dealing with their own responses to the year that was last week: thank you, from the bottom of my heart, thank you. and perhaps even more unexpectedly. to my dudes. the men, the incredible men who have sent me messages to say, ‚Äúi have to tell you, reading your story and your posts and the posts of too many women i know who have gone through similar things this week got to me. and today i spent 30 minutes talking to a guy i know about why it is important to believe women, that they are not doing it for publicity but to empower other survivors and to hopefully stop this from happening to someone else. i stood up for women today because of women like you in my life. keep fighting. keep posting. you are making a difference.‚Äù i just. i cannot tell you the difference you are making for me and every single other women by letting yourself feel the things we are sharing and being moved by it. my faith in humanity and myself was restored this weekend. and although i still know it‚Äôs on me to save myself. it is the most incredible thing on earth to know i can depend on you to help me. i don‚Äôt think i‚Äôve felt this whole in a long, long, long time. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è #metoo #believesurvivors #edrecovery #trauma #recovery #growth #ana #mia #edrecovered #eatingdisorderrecovery #ibelieveher #heforshe #friends

text:
ok... for all of you who blacked out your pic today. get ready because i'm not even half done. in less than 6 hours.. we will be in october, and you know what october is... domestic violence awareness month. so get ready those violet ribbons and get ready to do some me tooing of a different sort as we begin hashing up matters of domestic and intimate partner violence.

and we should be blunt about some of its greatest victims. children. childhood domestic violence which can include sexual violence is some of the most traumatic and damming forms of assault against another person. creating issues with self esteem, and depression, and anxiety and so on that can last an entire lifetime. making adult survivors of juvenile assault repeat customers of domestic violence or sexual violence well well into adulthood and beyond. 
we need a #metoo  movement for dv..... because this again is just more aggressive assault and violence against defenseless people that's given a public pass a lot.

#enddv #endsexualviolence

text:
i was a victim of abuse. physical, emotional, spiritual, and sexual.i say "was " because instead of letting it define me i am setting myself free.with this photoshoot i wrote words on my body used against me by all of my abusers. things used to hurt me, tear me down. words used to try to define me. words that were not truth. specifically not my truth.i was abused through the entirety of my life until this recent year.exes, my mother and anyone who felt they had right to my body,mind and spirit to harm me and do what they wanted.i once felt like a play thing. under the reign of others. i thought i deserved it. i thought it was my place. i no longer have to be afraid. my attackers are behind me. i never have to deal with them again. i now have an amazing boyfriend, and amazing friends, and a great support system in general. this wasn't always the case and in that iam lucky.unfortunately, this isn't the case for many men and women around the world.too many are still stuck with their abusers and sadly have no way out.i did this shoot to own it, to take my body back. to cleanse what i used to be. i was a victim and now i am strong. i may have once been a victim of abuse but, i realized i can be defined by new things. it is a rebirth and i am excited.i hope these photos inspire, and encourage. i hope they make you feel moved. i hope by sharing my raw vulnerability those still in these situations can feel either inspired to find help out of their situations or at least understand what they are going through is abuse. those who are free from their attackers in a physical sense or wherever you are in your situations. i hope these help you.
i wanted to represent in these photos the vulnerability, and fear of a victim but, also a deep determination to no longer be shackled to abuse.abuse will never end in the world entirely and for many they will never have a chance to purge their trauma or heal. but, the more we all work together the more we stand a fighting chance.i just want you all to know i love you. i love you so deeply. #abuse #growth #change #metoo #victim #youarenotalone #dontbeashamed #itsok #rape #survivor #selflove #trauma #recovery #strength

text:
after my episcopal church service i went to my husband‚Äôs evangelical church to wait for him in the cafe like i usually do. when i stepped out to use the restroom, i heard the sermon topic introduced. it was about potiphar‚Äôs wife. the one who falsely accused joseph of rape. this weekend of all weekends. right as it began, a friend texted me from inside the sanctuary and said, ‚Äúthe pastor swears this sermon was planned months in advance, but people around me are whispering that kavanaugh is the real victim.‚Äù after the sermon i went up to the pastor to share that with him. to his credit, he said that he didn‚Äôt mean for it to coincide with the hearings, that was just a coincidence, but false accusations do happen, and the church needs to be concerned about the truth. i said, ‚Äúpastor, with all due respect, figuring out the ‚Äòtruth‚Äô is not the church‚Äôs job. the church‚Äôs job is to support the victim. for a church that claims to want to make a difference in the community, it concerns me that it attracts so many people who automatically rushed to kavanaugh‚Äôs defense instead of ford‚Äôs.‚Äù it was a civil, if not somewhat disappointing conversation. i didn‚Äôt go all ‚Äúangry liberal feminist‚Äù on him (though it was tempting). he felt i interpreted the sermon through a ‚Äòfilter,‚Äô and maybe i did. but i have a feeling that that sermon was heard by more victims of assault than victims of false accusations. and statistics are pretty clear on which group is more common.

text: when i was a small ginger haired baby girl around the age i am in this picture, a man robbed me of a little bit of my innocence. i didn‚Äôt tell anyone the details of what happened for 12 years. shame, embarrassment, confusion, general weird feelings about the damn thing kept the words from coming out.  people don‚Äôt report sexual assault, or sexual misconduct, or inappropriate sexual behaviors for a myriad of reasons.  i am choosing to publicly speak my truth now to help anyone who may still be reluctant to speak theirs.  i believe you.  the #kavanaugh hearings have evoked strong emotions - both past and present. but for the first time, it feels overly tiresome and sad, simply just not worth it, to debate merits with people who see things differently from me. i‚Äôll keep talking because i know it‚Äôs the way forward, but the validity of her story is painfully corroborated by the lived experiences of all us who have ever been violated or even made just uncomfortable by a man.  i believe dr. blasey ford. #metoo

text:
this is so true and accurate!  think about it!  this is not a political post!  i do not know what happened!
my friends know i am a staunch advocate for victims and survivors!  i am going to take a class to become a sane (sexual assault nurse examiner) nurse.  i have my own #metoo story.  my mission has been to equip, empower and educate women to protect themselves and their families. 
i also personally know the effects of guilt by accusation; and how the burden of proof to prove wrong was all on the defendant even though there was no proof of anything and was all based on the accusation. 
i do know this üëá. i do know that 1 in 5 women are survivors of rape.

a violent crime occurs every 26 seconds

1 in 4 college age women are assaulted.

1 in 3 women experience domestic violence from their partners.

a child is abducted every 40 seconds.

i know this üëá is how many women live and we are fed up!

our lives truly begin the day we decide to do something!

text:
this is a detail show of the first sculpture i made for my upcoming show at @phosphorpgh first blood. it's based off of a painting by artemisia gentileschi depicting judith slaying holofernes. sometimes i question my inclination towards making feminist work, wondering if it's relevant but then shit like the kavanaugh nomination happen. gentileschi herself was raped and had to endure a very public and controversial trial where she was forced to describe her assault in detail. she was essentially tortured to prove she was telling the truth and after 7 months of trial they believed her. i've been thinking a lot about her and this painting and what christine blasey ford this week and how the fundamental structures of how we treat survivors and understand consent need to fucking change already. .
.
.

text:
this imagery came to me this week while connecting with a hurting sister.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i know not everyone can fight; there is a litany of reasons why and i respect those who can‚Äôt.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
that said, i have been so patient and so kind for so long. understanding so many i know with conservative values who wholeheartedly believe god‚Äôs design ‚Äúequal value; different roles,‚Äù for women and men. this view is called ‚Äúcomplementarianism‚Äù in the evangelical world.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i could write a doctorate on complementarian doctrine.  i studied it, watched it, lived it, and honestly breathed it for nearly two decades, from the tender age of 16 to 35.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i say this with kindness to those of you in that world, holding those beliefs: i will not force you to change your mind. i know you fully believe you are choosing to believe god. but in your personal beliefs you are contributing to a system that actively harms others, allowing a society that is abusive to keep its firm foundation on your back.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i say boldly: this is internalized misogyny. many who worship your same triune god find total equality in your same scriptures. those who created the system benefit from you being subservient to (mostly white middle- to upper-class) men. i know the churchgoing men are mostly true believers, too, who fully believe it is about jesus & not their ego. my husband was one.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
these men have you convinced that it‚Äôs god‚Äôs good will that you threaten & not their power when you reject their system. the opposite is true.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
you don‚Äôt have to leave the faith like me, or be unsure if you‚Äôll ever return to church like my husband. but the system works exactly as intended. it uses you & your faith to oppress your fellow humans for the benefit of a small group in power at the top.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
we all know what they look like. they look like all 11, mostly old, white men on the gop side of the senate judiciary committee. they overwhelm the majority of publicly held positions, company boards; they choose our entertainment, our taxes, what we can buy.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
they do not value us. they minimize our trauma & question our integrity when we speak.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
i‚Äôm done with nice. i am a warrior. i meant what i said: i will crush this patriarchy.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
üõ°üí™üèº

text: this cute little pup joined our family on friday. stupid me followed our local humane society on facebook and his picture was up there. there is so much #gsp in him, and we adore our sweet #indiebrame that i just couldn‚Äôt let his home be the shelter. he appears to be a #boingle or #poingle (same thing, different name. a pointer and beagle mix). his personality profile said that he has ‚Äòaggression towards men‚Äô (#metoo), so we have him in a trial basis while we see if we can work through that. he has no issues with brian and he‚Äôs fabulous with the kids and indie. he‚Äôs been super great, though he does seem to attach himself on to me. he has barked and growled at men on our walks, but we should be able to train that out of him. it makes me sad to think what he must have witnessed that he feels that he needs to be protective of the females in the house. so we are keeping our fingers crossed that ranger will adjust well with us!!

text:
i haven‚Äôt spoken about the recent current events involving our government because it‚Äôs hard to know what to say. 
what i can say is that i am heartbroken. i am heartbroken about the hatred and division. 
i have been praying and trying to be thoughtful, but mostly i have been trying to listen.
listen to the hurt. listen to the stories. listen to the cries. listen to the anger. 
remember that the person next you has a story. 
i have a story. i have survived sexual abuse, miscarriages, military deployments and heartache. i have overcome pain, struggles, and depression. i am strong and i have a voice. 
i encourage you to listen. step outside of your comfort zone and make an effort to learn how you can be a part of the change that this world needs.
your voice matters, speak your truth but also take the time to listen ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
i got in a fight...
.
with a punching bag at krav maga
.
i‚Äôve been practicing krav maga for one month now and i have some insights
.
1. i already feel more confident and stronger. how we show up in one area in life is how we show up in all areas. showing up in my krav maga class means yelling loudly to scare off my attacker. punching and kicking the shit out of this person to defend myself. making my body movements big and forceful. the instructors give me permission to act in a way that i‚Äôve never been taught as a woman. no room for being polite and nice
.
practicing this everyday has allowed me to feel more powerful in my everyday interactions with people. like i have a secret weapon and if anyone tries to fuck with me- they are going to be sorry

i like feeling this way
.
2. i didn‚Äôt realize how many weapons we already have on our body. elbows, knees, fingernails, feet, forehead, teeth...etc. we are powerful creatures that already have built in tools that can destroy and it‚Äôs pretty cool
.
3. my hands (as you can see in the picture), shins, feet and elbows are constantly bruised. i didn‚Äôt realize how easy it is to get physically hurt when you are trying to defend yourself and hurt someone else. grateful that i‚Äôm giving myself the next 6 months to allow my body to become stronger and tougher
.
4. attacking someone from seconds to minutes is so incredibly exhausting. i thought i was in shape from years of crossfit but apparently i‚Äôm not. when you are attacking, you use muscles in your body that you‚Äôve never used before. i‚Äôm so physically tired after every class
.
5. with the #metoo movement that is going on, i want to encourage every woman to think about doing krav maga. if you have a history of sexual abuse then this is a great way to get out your anger and feel vindicated. today i got to practice kicking a guy in the balls over and over again. (i didn‚Äôt really hit his balls, but just going through the motion felt great). also i love knowing now that if a man tries to rape me, i have a fair chance at protecting myself and fighting back. how fucking amazing is that?!

text: giving birth at home is rapidly becoming a more popular birthing option for families in the united states. women are choosing to birth at home for many reasons, including lower rates of intervention and more personalized, holistic care. although the number of women who actually give birth at home is still very small (less than 2%), home birth has certainly gained a lot of attention (and controversy!) in the last few years. despite the frenzy, home birth is an often misunderstood and misrepresented option, rife with stereotypes and fear based misinformation. the reality of homebirth is that it recognizes that the power source of birth is the birthing mother and respectfully, safely and attentively allows the process to unfold organically while supporting the experience. women can have natural hospital birth, of course, but re: post partum care, the model of care you receive when you give birth at home greatly differs from what happens in the larger medical system. instead of the 48 hour hospital stay and the perfunctory six-week visit, your care with a home birth midwife will be more frequent and more detailed. different midwives have different ways of practicing postpartum, but you'll most likely receive multiple home visits to check up on you and your baby in that first critical week postpartum to help with healing, nursing and the transition to motherhood. babies are skin to skin with mothers, no interruptions to the immediate bonding/transitioning  of mother/baby and no nicu to contend with. many families do not realize that babies are the ward of the hospital until they are officially discharged and decisions are often made without consenting parents. at home the care continuum is never broken. priceless food for thought. üì∏ @shawnalstanley #wholeninewellness #ittakesavillage #birthwithoutfear #birthisnatural #homebirth #birthworker #doula

i don‚Äôt care who you are, what gender or race or sexuality, sexual assault is not due to what you‚Äôre wearing, it is not your fault, and no one should ever tell you different.
to anyone who has been affected by sexual assault, you are not alone, and you didn‚Äôt do anything to deserve it. to everyone, let‚Äôs stop victim shaming and keep letting everyone who needs us know that we‚Äôre here for them.
this is part of a way larger conversation. let‚Äôs keep talking. #metoo

text:
‚Äî
to care for those, who once cared for us, is one of the highest honours. ‚Äî
my momma
my lord
my shield.
‚Äî
some days i curl up in my blanket with my cats and cry. there are moments i‚Äôm too numb to move, too traumatized to speak, to disturbed to sleep. the death of a parent is an immaculate blow. she was in such discomfort and mental turmoil it became inhumane to watch. due to all the drugs, and the progression of cancer in her body, i watched her slowly mentally and physically deteriorate. it was excruciating to see. she saw spiders crawling in her skin, she thought people were raping her, she would gasp for air and cry that she couldn‚Äôt breath. i‚Äôve never felt so helpless. i gave the doctor the go-ahead to put her under but i didn‚Äôt realize that those moments were my last. july 14th 2017- january 1st 2018 was a fog. after she passed, i was distraught and turned to substances. i didn‚Äôt want to think, i didn‚Äôt know how to live, i was alone and lost after what i saw and experienced. my mental health became so severe‚Äî  i didn‚Äôt go to the gym, i couldn‚Äôt leave my apartment. i worked acutely with mental health at the time, and because mine was suffering, i didn‚Äôt feel i could perform my duties effectively/efficiently. i stopped going to work. i couldn‚Äôt compartmentalize what was going on. i moved my kitchen and toiletries into my room and stayed there for months. living became difficult, i couldn‚Äôt afford food on my plate so i‚Äôd visit martha‚Äôs table. i was preparing for homelessness and i planned to sleep in my car and shower/hygiene at planet fitness. i still held my position in security but mentally couldn‚Äôt go. i was desperate for money and was debating a position offered to me at the plaza.
‚Äî
when you feel like giving up. remember how far you‚Äôve come. remember why you held on for so long. grief comes in waves...sometimes the water is calm, and sometimes it‚Äôs overwhelming. all we can do is learn to swim.
.
.
.
.

obliteration 
extermination 
to remove the scum from the earth

text:
a woman's humanity should not be contingent on her relationship to a man.
.
.
.
i started this quilt several months ago with leftover scraps from bed sheets. the initial cutting and piecing i did quickly in a flurry of rage and have been adding hand quilting off and on over the past few months. it was inspired by the statements of "support" some men make when yet another story of female struggle hits the news. i do not have sons or brothers. i was raised by my mother and i am unmarried. it has been made clear to me my entire life that the fact that i do not have these relationships with men makes me vulnerable. i and every woman deserve the right to feel safe because we're people. full stop.
.
#timesup #metoo #believewomen #quilt #quiltersofinstagram #quiltsasprotest #fiberart #sewing

text:
i was a victim of abuse. physical, emotional, spiritual, and sexual.i say "was " because instead of letting it define me i am setting myself free.with this photoshoot i wrote words on my body used against me by all of my abusers. things used to hurt me, tear me down. words used to try to define me. words that were not truth. specifically not my truth.i was abused through the entirety of my life until this recent year.exes, my mother and anyone who felt they had right to my body,mind and spirit to harm me and do what they wanted.i once felt like a play thing. under the reign of others. i thought i deserved it. i thought it was my place. i no longer have to be afraid. my attackers are behind me. i never have to deal with them again. i now have an amazing boyfriend, and amazing friends, and a great support system in general. this wasn't always the case and in that iam lucky.unfortunately, this isn't the case for many men and women around the world.too many are still stuck with their abusers and sadly have no way out.i did this shoot to own it, to take my body back. to cleanse what i used to be. i was a victim and now i am strong. i may have once been a victim of abuse but, i realized i can be defined by new things. it is a rebirth and i am excited.i hope these photos inspire, and encourage. i hope they make you feel moved. i hope by sharing my raw vulnerability those still in these situations can feel either inspired to find help out of their situations or at least understand what they are going through is abuse. those who are free from their attackers in a physical sense or wherever you are in your situations. i hope these help you.
i wanted to represent in these photos the vulnerability, and fear of a victim but, also a deep determination to no longer be shackled to abuse.abuse will never end in the world entirely and for many they will never have a chance to purge their trauma or heal. but, the more we all work together the more we stand a fighting chance.i just want you all to know i love you. i love you so deeply. #abuse #growth #change #metoo #victim #youarenotalone #dontbeashamed #itsok  #rape #survivor #selflove #trauma #recovery #strength

text:
i was a victim of abuse. physical, emotional, spiritual, and sexual.i say "was " because instead of letting it define me i am setting myself free.with this photoshoot i wrote words on my body used against me by all of my abusers. things used to hurt me, tear me down. words used to try to define me. words that were not truth. specifically not my truth.i was abused through the entirety of my life until this recent year.exes, my mother and anyone who felt they had right to my body,mind and spirit to harm me and do what they wanted.i once felt like a play thing. under the reign of others. i thought i deserved it. i thought it was my place. i no longer have to be afraid. my attackers are behind me. i never have to deal with them again. i now have an amazing boyfriend, and amazing friends, and a great support system in general. this wasn't always the case and in that iam lucky.unfortunately, this isn't the case for many men and women around the world.too many are still stuck with their abusers and sadly have no way out.i did this shoot to own it, to take my body back. to cleanse what i used to be. i was a victim and now i am strong. i may have once been a victim of abuse but, i realized i can be defined by new things. it is a rebirth and i am excited.i hope these photos inspire, and encourage. i hope they make you feel moved. i hope by sharing my raw vulnerability those still in these situations can feel either inspired to find help out of their situations or at least understand what they are going through is abuse. those who are free from their attackers in a physical sense or wherever you are in your situations. i hope these help you.
i wanted to represent in these photos the vulnerability, and fear of a victim but, also a deep determination to no longer be shackled to abuse.abuse will never end in the world entirely and for many they will never have a chance to purge their trauma or heal. but, the more we all work together the more we stand a fighting chance.i just want you all to know i love you. i love you so deeply. #abuse #growth #change #metoo #victim #youarenotalone #dontbeashamed #itsok  #rape #survivor #selflove #trauma #recovery #strength

text:
i was a victim of abuse. physical, emotional, spiritual, and sexual.i say "was " because instead of letting it define me i am setting myself free.with this photoshoot i wrote words on my body used against me by all of my abusers. things used to hurt me, tear me down. words used to try to define me. words that were not truth. specifically not my truth.i was abused through the entirety of my life until this recent year.exes, my mother and anyone who felt they had right to my body,mind and spirit to harm me and do what they wanted.i once felt like a play thing. under the reign of others. i thought i deserved it. i thought it was my place. i no longer have to be afraid. my attackers are behind me. i never have to deal with them again. i now have an amazing boyfriend, and amazing friends, and a great support system in general. this wasn't always the case and in that iam lucky.unfortunately, this isn't the case for many men and women around the world.too many are still stuck with their abusers and sadly have no way out.i did this shoot to own it, to take my body back. to cleanse what i used to be. i was a victim and now i am strong. i may have once been a victim of abuse but, i realized i can be defined by new things. it is a rebirth and i am excited.i hope these photos inspire, and encourage. i hope they make you feel moved. i hope by sharing my raw vulnerability those still in these situations can feel either inspired to find help out of their situations or at least understand what they are going through is abuse. those who are free from their attackers in a physical sense or wherever you are in your situations. i hope these help you.
i wanted to represent in these photos the vulnerability, and fear of a victim but, also a deep determination to no longer be shackled to abuse.abuse will never end in the world entirely and for many they will never have a chance to purge their trauma or heal. but, the more we all work together the more we stand a fighting chance.i just want you all to know i love you. i love you so deeply. #abuse #growth #change #metoo #victim #youarenotalone #dontbeashamed #itsok  #rape #survivor #selflove #trauma #recovery #strength

text:
i was a victim of abuse. physical, emotional, spiritual, and sexual.i say "was " because instead of letting it define me i am setting myself free.with this photoshoot i wrote words on my body used against me by all of my abusers. things used to hurt me, tear me down. words used to try to define me. words that were not truth. specifically not my truth.i was abused through the entirety of my life until this recent year.exes, my mother and anyone who felt they had right to my body,mind and spirit to harm me and do what they wanted.i once felt like a play thing. under the reign of others. i thought i deserved it. i thought it was my place. i no longer have to be afraid. my attackers are behind me. i never have to deal with them again. i now have an amazing boyfriend, and amazing friends, and a great support system in general. this wasn't always the case and in that iam lucky.unfortunately, this isn't the case for many men and women around the world.too many are still stuck with their abusers and sadly have no way out.i did this shoot to own it, to take my body back. to cleanse what i used to be. i was a victim and now i am strong. i may have once been a victim of abuse but, i realized i can be defined by new things. it is a rebirth and i am excited.i hope these photos inspire, and encourage. i hope they make you feel moved. i hope by sharing my raw vulnerability those still in these situations can feel either inspired to find help out of their situations or at least understand what they are going through is abuse. those who are free from their attackers in a physical sense or wherever you are in your situations. i hope these help you.
i wanted to represent in these photos the vulnerability, and fear of a victim but, also a deep determination to no longer be shackled to abuse.abuse will never end in the world entirely and for many they will never have a chance to purge their trauma or heal. but, the more we all work together the more we stand a fighting chance.i just want you all to know i love you. i love you so deeply. #abuse #growth #change #metoo #victim #youarenotalone #dontbeashamed #itsok  #rape #survivor #selflove #trauma #recovery #strength

text:
tw: assault

i want to start this post by saying that i appreciate the concept of "blacking out" your profile. a concept which shows support/solidarity for femmes/female oriented people is incredible.

this is why i will not be blacking out my profile:

i am done silencing myself. 
i am over apologizing for my personality.

i am a loud, straight forward, intense woman. 
i am queer. 
i am a sex worker.

i am a performer.

i have been assaulted, raped, and abused(and i was blamed for all of it) 
i will take up space. 
i choose to vocalize myself, when i want to.

i recognize that my poc friends/members of the community are persecuted for their "blackness", and that by "blacking out" something (like my profile) i am inherently promoting "invisibility" and delegitimzing them being seen.

not every survivor will want to be vocal about their experience. yes it takes "courage" to come forward but that does not making someone a coward for not speaking out. it could be 5 minutes, 20 months, 30 years or never. the choice to come forward is simply that. a choice. the burden and re-traumatizing experience of sharing details should never be expected. ever. 
i stand openly and honestly. i choose to be seen and to be heard.

i recognize my privilege and i will use it (with positive intent) to stand and be vocal when people feel they cannot.

i will not silence myself for the sake of "showing what it would be like without me". we already know our society doesn't care about our rights, our freedoms as women(not just cis gendered either). so, why play into their  invisibility? 
i am strong. i am beautiful. i am a survivor. and i will not be invisible.

#survivor #strong #femmessupportingfemmes #solidarity #metoo #visibility #sexworker #sexworkersarepeople #yesastripper
name: Miss Pamela Voorhees

text:
death rides shotgun (in the kidnapper's car)

my best friend blew his brains out 
after an apocalyptic dream (in which we met again)
i entertained death, at least the thought of it
while walking up san vicente to my apartment on sunset
a  car pulled up & a smallish man whispered something about directions
my gut told me to walk away, but i leaned over
he pulled me in the passenger side of the car
slammed the lock down, held his arm against my breast
he said "i have a .38 under the seat - i'm gonna kill you if you don't do what i say"
i swear he must have felt my heart pounding
so intense this was, i had not felt my heart ever beat so strong & so fierce
i left my body 
i floated above & saw myself dead 
my loved ones wondering
"how could she have been so stupid?"
"how was this man creature able to snuff her out?"
i calmed a bit & tried a conversation with the kidnapper:
"so, where do you live? do you have a sister?"
"you can come to my house, it's okay, i live on sunset & san vicente"
he paused, then continued on with his threats: "i'm gonna kill you if you don't do what i say"
he drove for at least an hour 
going from crazy talk to silence to threats
i didn't know where i was, i knew it was late, but los angeles is a big place, i could be anywhere
my intense fear was controlled until he stopped the car, turned off the engine and said in a soft voice "now, take off your panties"
there was a split second when i wanted to cry & beg for my life: or fight
no rational thinking, i went crazy - i was scratching & kicking & screaming trying to get the fuck put of that car
he kept reaching under his seat, i didn't care if he shot me, i would rather be dead then to be raped by this asshole:
he pulled out a knife
at this point, i knew every move he was making
(i was told controlled fear = a lot of adrenaline)
super strong i became & blocked his knife, getting stabbed in the hand & the leg:
then the knife broke:
i was eyeball to eyeball, fist to fist with my attacker & i screamed: "i wanna live!"
"i wanna live motherfucker"
maybe he got off on the fight, maybe no one had gone toe to toe before, whatever 
he opened the door & told me he'd shoot me if i looked back
at which

text: there are a few things that come to mind when i look at my two sweet, kind, loving boys. as a mother of boys, i hope and pray that i can raise them and teach them to treat women well, to respect them, to listen to them, to empower them, to support them, and to always be good humans. i hope that they will be a force for good in this world and make waves, even if it‚Äôs scary. i hope that they stand up for others, even when it‚Äôs hard. i hope that they continue to see positive role models and eventually become one themselves. i hope they know i love them forever and always. #boyswillbegoodhumans

text_retweet:
i wanted to repost a couple of things i've been thinking about this weekend...
first, i would like to share my friend, meghan chase's incredible recent projects, "tied in knots" and "we get sharper." these are ongoing performance pieces in which the artist used kitchen knives to knit aimless, endless strands as a commentary on the ways that women ritualistically perform actions to protect themselves from potential danger (such as checking the back seat of their cars for intruders or carrying their keys between their fingers.)
a few hours after seeing images of meghan's work, i saw some of the responses to danielle muscato's thought experiment on twitter in which she asked the question, "what would you do if all men had a 9 pm curfew?" thousands of women responded, "i would go for an evening walk." i think it is important for men to be aware of and be more empathetic towards the fear that women have lived with for so long that it now feels normal. young girls are given advice about how to safely navigate the world that is eventually validated as they get older through experience. meghan chase writes, "women learn to expect violence and occupy their body differently and navigate space based on that expectation."
personally, i love traveling alone, camping and hiking alone, walking and running at night, and buying used items on letgo that i pick up in person.  i usually don't let my fears keep me from doing these things, and i receive a lot of criticism for that.  i wish i lived in a world where women didn't have to be so afraid of being alone.
#metoo #feministart #ibelieveher #contemporaryart #knittingwithsteakknives #meghanchase

text: friends... i have been relatively quiet this past year about the me too movement and this crazy circus called the usa. i‚Äôve had wounds reopened that i swear just healed. i‚Äôve been reminded that the enemy is sometimes someone you love. i‚Äôve driven out to the middle of nowhere so i could just scream and cry in peace. i‚Äôve been reminded that i can not trust some of the people i love. i‚Äôve been angry. i‚Äôve been hurt... but more importantly, i‚Äôm taking the time to own my shit. this book is seriously amazing. think of it as a tool in your life toolbox. grief compounds, and healing is circular. take care of yourself first. find your peace again. and keep this book handy. #selfcare #grief #griefrecovery #thegriefrecoveryhandbook #bookstagram #onmybookshelf #healyourself #lovethisbook #checkitout #library #metoo #metoomovement #youcandoit #bebetter #changeforthegood #loveyourself #trauma #ptsd #helpyourself #aslightpause

text:
this post is not political. this post is intended to shine a spotlight on an evil that exists in our society. 
i live in a very small town. it‚Äôs often thought that stuff like this doesn‚Äôt happen in a small town. it does. it absolutely does. we are not immune. we are not immune. 
i take precautions every single day and so should you. am i peeved off that i have to? yep! am i peeved off that i have to teach my way too young daughters that they have to? yep! 
it‚Äôs okay to be peeved off ‚Äî don‚Äôt apologize for it! take that anger and use it to make change. starting in your own home. 
parents of boys. 
parents of girls. 
change starts at home. today.

text:
sexual assault and harassment has been becoming more publicly discussed in this past year more so then any other. it is the time for women to come forward and reveal their own experiences that they have gone through and their ways of coping as well as reaching out to get help. with the me too movement and thousands of sexual assault victims coming out, they have finally been given the voices that they‚Äôve deserved. 
if you have not been caught up on the recent news, then let me tell you of a current event that‚Äôs going on. 
our president donald trump, who has had 19 sexual assault allegations on him, nominated a man named brett kavanaugh to be seated on the supreme court. recently, a woman named christine ford has come forward and revealed that she was sexually assaulted by kavanaugh while the two were still in high school, which was 36 years ago. ford has finally been able to speak out about her experience, and she not only spoke for herself but she spoke up for the victims around the world who are too afraid to come forward. but the shocking thing is that this brave woman who represents so many people in the world, is getting death threats and hate and was even told by our own president that her story is a hoax created by the democrats as a way to delay the nomination. this is just another representation of how woman and sexual assault victims are treated in this country. they are treated as if what they have been through doesn‚Äôt matter and that men will continue to be free of consequences from their actions. senator cory booker states, ‚Äú...how we deal with survivors who come forward right now is unacceptable. the way we deal with this unfortunately allows for the continued darkness of this culture to exist.‚Äù as a young girl, i do not want to live in a world where this is acceptable, where men in power are allowed to get away with anything. i shouldn‚Äôt have to fear living my life or calling the wrong attention to myself. no man should be able to get away with something like that. so in order for our country to improve and to lower down the percentage of sexual assault victims, we cannot let men in power like brett kavanaugh get away with acts like this.

text:
with everything going on in the world these days i‚Äôve felt full of gratitude for the strong, beautiful, and amazing men in my life who have shown me what it means to be a real man
~~~~~
real men who where there to listen, validate my hurt, and catch my tears after being sexually aggressed
~~~~~~~~
real men who encouraged and empowered me to stand strong, speak the truth, report, and find support.
~~~~~~~~~
real men that showed me what real love and respect is and that i am worthy of it
~~~~~~~~
and the real man who was my aggressor and now friend, because years later he had the courage and heart to reach out to apologize, speak the truth that his actions where a violation of me as a human, and thank me for being strong enough to let him know the hurt he caused and threaten to report if it didn‚Äôt stop. ~~~~~~~
facts:
1) these are real men and they do exist!
2) i am part of the statistic that at least 31% of women who have experienced dv do not report it to authorities
3)healing is possible 
4) changing cultural norms starts with you
~~~~~~~~~
this weekend getting lost in the pnw forests and coastlines mother nature reminded me how resilient life is! death and decay, pain and wounds, lead to new growth, rich nutrients, and beauty!
let this moment in history be a time of growth, beauty, rich connection, and celebration of resiliency!

text:
i am in the very privileged position to not have experienced real harm...ever. but a lot of women have and will. we (men & women) need to stop treating women that come forward like the criminal!!! it is not okay to point fingers at them, discuss what they might have done wrong to cause this to themselves, nor imputing something stupid like politics, hate or disrespect to them. 
there are other perpetrators too, but first of all the strong white man needs to realise that women are not goods. 
in regards to the story at issue, as mentioned i have not experienced harm, but the smaller version - dirty looks, weird sexual comments covered as compliments (on a highly proffesional level)- yes. and i can assure everyone if once that made you feel really, really uncomfortable, you‚Äôll remember it exactly. 
sexual assault is a crime, that causes trauma for life and not a somewhat trivial offence. read and listen to @thordiselva for better understanding. #metoo #thordiselva #consentfirst #listentowomen #sexualassault #timesup

text:
i just called my daughter, age 17, who has only been out of my sight an hour. "i just want to make sure you know if you ever tell me you were assaulted in any way,  i will believe you.  i will stand with you.  tell your friends i will believe them,  too." an american is sexually assaulted every 98 seconds.  63% of these assaults are never reported.  people keep posting they are afraid for their sons,  that some girl might spread a lie and ruin his life.  only 2% of sexual assault claims are false.  raise your son to understand consent and there's no need to worry about him being accused of assault.  but if he is accused,  he most likely did it. 
however,  statements fearing what will happen  to sons is part of why girls are afraid to come forward. (boys/men are also sexually assaulted and should also be believed,  of course.) photo snapped two years ago today as my daughter and i waited for hours in the hot sun to try to see @hillaryclinton speak.  we didn't get in. the crowd was large.  i still believe #lovetrumpshate.

statistics from national sexual violence resource center.

text: take care of yourself lovelies. this selfie is a throwback from my week alone up in the puget sound, when my schedule was sauna, sleep, and hike. cultivating peace is necessary. we can run ourselves ragged if we aren‚Äôt conscious of the tension between input and output. this week has been trying and triggering due to the amount of uncovered trauma around sexual assault.üåπüå∫üßò‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüî•i have been trying to make space for honoring the rage and sadness of myself, and for the women i work with, and allowing for the awareness of a greater system of oppression that enable these sexual trauma narratives to be so common. i am grateful for the strength of women right now and for the #metoo movement, and for the connections i have to the women in my own family and close friends. i am also grateful for the amount of light that is being shed on to sexual trauma, because shame can be one of the most difficult emotions to experience, and shame flourishes in darkness and in silence. if you can make space for someone else‚Äôs pain right now, there are folks that need that. if you have too much of your own coming up, honor that. pause. breathe. experience. process. connect. reflect. release. #selfcare #traumacare #metoo #metoomovement2018 #ibelieveher #ibelievewomen #thankyoudrford #honoryourself #honoryouremotions

text:
#metoo part ii

i appreciate all the support and the love that‚Äôs come my way after sharing my #metoo story this friday. 
but there‚Äôs an important message in that story  that doesn‚Äôt get talked about much. 
the aftermath. 
because bad things happen to all of us. bad things happen to good people all of the time. 
and while i do believe in the possibility of an ideal world of where bad stuff happens to good people, i think there are so many necessary lessons to be learned from within darkness. 
what makes people truly remarkable are the choices they make despite the bad stuff. choosing to honor themselves over the trauma. choosing to take action in service of something greater than themselves. choosing that temporary discomfort of growth to reach for something higher. choosing to be happy and thriving instead of scared and stuck. 
making those choices to be greater than the things that have happened in our past, to be greater than what is currently around you in your life and environment is not easy. 
trauma forces us to stay in the known. it leaves us believing new and unknown things are bad. and so we avoid them. we end up stuck in old patterns of feeling believing and living. soon we are so locked in our own personal purgatory- feeling lost and despondent, suffering silently. 
there are ways to unlock those patterns. and it means stepping out of what has become familiar and past the illusions of safety. it‚Äôs allowing yourself to explore the unknown, and your own wildness within. 
i‚Äôve made choices every day since that moment 3.5 years ago. that experience no longer torments me. it no longer makes decisions for me. 
because i decided was going to be more than a victim- that i was going to be the heroine of my life, and i was going to do whatever it took to get there.

movement became my alchemy. it changed my life from the inside out. it allowed me to move through fear and pain and find salvation. to face my victimization and transform it into power and strength. 
it allowed me to see so much more of myself and so much more opportunity and beauty in the world around me. 
but most of all, it‚Äôs allowed me to live my best life.

it allowed me to see so much more of myself and so much more oppounity and beauty in the world around me. 
but most of all, it‚Äôs allowed me to live my best life.

text:
the state house all lit up last night ‚ú®
while taking this photo, a beautiful little girl came up to me and asked if i would help her do the same pose. we snapped the second photo and spoke for a moment, and as i looked up at the words being projected behind us showing strength for women, my heart warmed and my eyes teared. providence was supporting #breastcancerawareness month, but it took on a whole new meaning with everything happening in our country currently. i think we should all take a moment today to put politics and parties aside and truly give thought to what we believe is right and good in our hearts. i myself am disappointed in america for many reasons right now. i may never see the changes that i believe should be made, but that doesn‚Äôt mean we can stop standing up for what we believe in. this is not about us and our time here right now, this is about the future for little girls like her. i believe it is wrong for women to not have control over their bodies. that young people are scared for their lives when they go to school. that beautiful children are being locked up in cages. but this does not come down to what my political stance is. this is about human decency and kindness. so i urge you to put yourself in others shoes, reflect on your values and use your voice! and vote! üíó #providence #rhodeisland #womensrights #believesurvivors #timesup #metoo #vote and most of all #bekind ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
my apologies to shakespeare. i‚Äôm capitalizing on his infinite wisdom to make a point. the loudest voice in the room, the shouters and spitters and fist-wavers and red-in-the-face demanders, are often the liars. bluster doesn‚Äôt make you right. angry demonstrations aren‚Äôt proof that you‚Äôve been wronged. a judge, let alone a supreme court justice, should know this better than anyone.
*
if you have been triggered by the recent hearings, i hope that you know that - even if you choose not to share your own experience of trauma in a loud and public forum - you are heard. because, in my experience, it is the quietest ones who have been hurt the most. go at your own pace. your whispers are scream enough.
*
*

text:
what is surfacing for woman with the #metoomovement is a collective trauma - generations of woman who have been denied a voice, rights and access to power. 
figures from the crime survey for england and wales tell us 1 in 5 women and 1 in 20 men in the uk have survived some kind of sexual assault. 
83% of cases are never reported and less than 5% of cases that are prosecuted lead to conviction. 
dr christine blasey ford had 15 strong female friends with her at the hearing . all the women flew in together , stayed together and offered her their love, kindness, friendship, encouragement and support . 
i also want to acknowledge all the supportive male voices, the comments and responses that have been loud and clear on social media condoning this current wave of toxic masculinity. men calling out for a much needed #malerevolution . #metoo #christineblaseyford #kavanaughhearings #collectivetrauma

text:
a good wine is like a good woman. just sit down, shut up, and listen. listen for once.

this is how i thought about blind tasting when i started seriously studying for somm certification. don't talk over the wine, don't tell the glass what you want to find, just let it speak to you. sometimes, as with the women and femmes in my life, i don't always listen as well as i should. but we are always learning, and should never stop trying to improve.

so, to the matter at hand: men are the ones who need to be sitting down and listening right now. and it is men that i invite to share this image as if to say, "i am listening, i am ready to learn." we need women to speak out. we need nonbinary people to speak out, regardless of how they present. but if you identify as a man, it is your responsility to create an environment where those who have been silent for so long can feel comfortable speaking, because we have had the stage for quite some time.

even the men who are also survivors of sexual abuse and assault, i feel very strongly that this is the best way for us to express #metoo at this moment. we need to hear those voices too. but right now us men all need to sit down.

to everyone else, i'm listening. to that end, this will be my last post for a few days. in the meantime, raise my glass to you #winenotbeer

#men #taketheblack #imlistening #ibelieveher #believewomen #believesurvivors #noterfsnoswerfs #womensrights #transrights #nonbinary #shoutoutnotblackout #blackout #women #alwayslearning #sexualassault #sexualabuse #istandwithdrford #wine #somm

text:
i use my cards not as devination, but as a link to my subconcious, to my own inner knowing and wisdom.  it is for me to actually see what i already know deep within me. 
a few weeks ago i drew cards that were all about making a hard decision, allowing change, and the grief that will come with the metamorphosis.

text:
it‚Äôs hard to realize codependence is hurting you, when it‚Äôs so favored by the world around you.
. 
they will call you an angel, a savior even. they will only come to you, because you‚Äôre always there. when they are suffering, you are who they need. they know you will bail them out, take them back, take them in, easily forgive and forget. and they do this, not because they love you, but because you love them. more than they can.  more than yourself.  more than your own need to be truly loved.
. 
but then there comes a point where you have nothing left to give. 
you‚Äôre tired of not receiving what you need in life. you‚Äôve done everything, changed and compromised yourself to the point of despair, and it‚Äôs still not enough. .
if this sounds familiar, please consider joining me in my soul family membership group this month.  we are doing a 5 part live coaching series on ‚Äúending codependence‚Äù for good.
. ‚≠êÔ∏è our first session begins this monday evening @8pm cst. .

you can attend the live session with me on facebook, where i can address your specific needs, or sign up for access to the archive.
.
register now and we can become better at love together. (link in bio.)
.

really enjoyed my first visit to @wigtownbookfest both as an author and as a member of the audience.

she was a 65 year old woman who wasn‚Äôt believed years ago when she spoke out about being raped by her ex husband. 
she was so ashamed as she spoke to me, but decided it was time to get help and finally speak and deal with it

it‚Äôs never too late to find your voice and break your silence. there is always hope

text:
dear sons,

i hope to raise you with honesty, humility, and respect toward women. may you see yourselves as equals and never take for granted your male status. we hope to raise you knowing you have a responsibility with the privilege you carry, but did not earn; a privilege our society will place on you. my prayer for you as you age, is to become advocates; that you see injustice and run towards it and not away from it. i hope you know how loved you both are, and that because of your confidence in this love, you in turn will love others well; by speaking up on their behalf, respecting women and their bodies, and advocating when someone speaks of injustice done to them. you are our future. be world changers. 
all my love.
.
.
.
.
.
.
