text:
about about 6 months ago i made the difficult decision to abandon the company i had spent over 3 years building, because i finally realized i didn‚Äôt have to keep thinking that an exchange of sexual harassment for money was the norm.

it was one particularly cold march night when a man requested a 20 minute pedicab ride before being dropped at his hotel. he spent the first five minutes trying to hold a drunken conversation until that wasn‚Äôt enough for him and he started grab my butt and waist. after several attempts to pry his hands off of me and politely asking him to stop i decided to get more assertive and head back to drop him off at his hotel early‚Äîthreatening to tase him every time he touched me. once we arrived at the hotel i quickly dismounted my bike and made my distance so he could no longer grab hold of me. he spent the next 20 minutes graphically talking about when (not if) we would kiss and fuck and how nice it would be for him‚Äîall while i begged him to leave. he refused to leave my bike. the only thing stopping me from dragging him out was the fear of his hands grabbing me again. i tried to call his most recent contact, his friend in the hotel room, to tell him of the harassment, asking him to retrieve his friend and compensate me. his friend literally laughed at me and hung up. i eventually left him unattended to ask a hotel staff to assist me and that‚Äôs when he made his run. i caught him by the elevator to demand to be compensated for my time. that‚Äôs when he grabbed me again, by the shoulder, and whispered in my ear, letting me know of his anger, and assuring me that i was ‚Äúasking for it‚Äù and he knew ‚Äúwhat i really was‚Äù. let me remind you it was 30 degrees out and me ‚Äúasking for it‚Äù was wearing two pairs of pants and three jackets. i eventually settled on a discounted rate, feeling dirty, wanting to be compensated for my discomfort yet at the same time not wanting to be paid for ass-grabbing (making me then some sort of sex worker). and incidents like this happened all the time. but this particular night was the last straw and the night i told mark i would be transitioning out of the industry. 
#metoo

text:
this is my new friend, meaghan and part of her family. 
before being baptized today meaghan shared part of her story. 
she is one, among many, who has been sexually abused by a single man. 
she blamed herself. 
she thought she needed to fix herself to feel worthy enough for god to love her. 
then god broke through showing his love for her as she is and how he wants to make something beautiful out of the pieces. 
so she was baptized today as her husband and oldest son watched and laughed (her 2 year old thought it was funny she was dunked üòÇ). we also watched, smiled and cried as a church listening to her strength and story of god making something beautiful from the broken. 
she told carrie and i she isn‚Äôt whole yet but she‚Äôs grateful to be a part of church that is with her and for her. 
#woodsidedetroit #metoo

text:
these are beautiful flowers from the hub who brought some love and light to my week. between the weather changing and being brutal on those of us with chronic illness. there is all the kavanaugh blasey ford debacle. this has all been extremely hard on me(and all survivors alike). i joined the speakers bureau of rainn last year. reason was to share my stories of being molested and raped and more as a teen. i once again have shared my story with #whyididntreport. we share our stories to educate and let those know they are not alone. unfortunately thou that sometimes comes with pain of reliving those events. ptsd yes not only those who served our country but those of us who have suffered unspeakable horrors. if speaking up is somehow in any way even if it‚Äôs small baby steps going to help, if somehow make those who find it unbelievable believable, even if it takes years to change perception and laws we will go through pain again again. that is what makes us brave fierce warrior women!!! üíñ‚ù§Ô∏èüíú #ibelieveyou #youarenotalone #survivorsunite #actwithrainn

text_retweet: i got to be a part of a live art installation yesterday! @aplaceintheuniverse alicia i love your heart and your vision. you are her was created to bring attention to and spark conversation about the rate at which college women are and will be sexually assaulted in their college years. it is almost 1 in 4 college women. let that sink in for a minute. so as you are reposting and sharing all the horrible posts that have been flying around in the last week take a minute and think about how many women you know. now line them up and almost 25% of them have been or will be sexually assaulted. and guess what, they haven‚Äôt told you. and for many it happened decades ago or months ago or whatever time period you want to attach to it and they still haven‚Äôt told you or anyone else for that matter. and that is allowed. and it is also ok for those women to say something when they feel more comfortable doing so. even if that means ruining the career of a politician or a doctor or a coach or whatever that man/men went onto be. this is so incredibly prevalent in our society. i know so many friends and neighbors that have a story. think before you share. think before you endorse. think before you get an opinion. women find your voice and tell a friend. let them support you. #metoo #sexualassault #endit #women #voice #justice #change #womenarepeople #notobjects #create #beautifulthings

text:
a while ago i wrote a thing about one of my dearest friends, who has lived through so many things that no one should ever experience, and yet has remained so kind, and careful, and loving, throughout. this is a very female strength, and with the events of the past few weeks, i keep thinking about it, about the things that women carry. i know so many women who have lived through true horrors, who carry crosses they should never have had to, and carry them with grace, with love, with empathy. i know so many women who are so unbelievably strong despite being told and shown since birth that their strength, their trauma, is less-than. so many women who go through their days gasping for breath. we have come a long way for women, especially in america, but not far enough, and trauma is cross generational. this is especially true for black and brown women in america, for all woc, who carry burdens i can‚Äôt even fathom. they have been doubly failed and this too has weighed on my mind. i see women attacking each other, women who say terrible things about another‚Äôs trauma, about their credibility, women who turn cold. i also see an unbelievable network of survivors- because we are all survivors of something- who have reached out to each other, quietly, whispered names in prayer, who grit teeth and link arms and bleed openly in an elevator in front of cameras to change the fate of the country, of all of us. a great and terrible burden, a great and terrible beauty.
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

text:
once upon a time, i believed in rainbows and unicorns. today? i blacked out my profile on facebook, but then i realized those that needed the message wouldn't get it. so, i'll compromise. 
and i will tell you #metoo. i'm a survivor of domestic abuse. of date rape. of sexual molestation. 
two at the hands of women. yes, women. the molestation came at the hands of my neighbor's father. i told my mother anyway. 
she believed me. he went to jail. 
the other two? both women. i told others. cai believed me. she came for me in shreveport. she got me out of there. i. went. back. 
i went back. 
it took me a total of five years to get out. but in the end? she left me. said she didn't like who i made her be. who. i. made. her. be. 
i believed that for many years. 
the color is gone from my picture, but not from my world. i'm much stronger now. 
if you are in an abusive situation, stop making excuses for them, for why you are staying, for any of it. get out. take what you can and get out. there's always help. even when you don't think there is. 
blacking out profiles? it does nothing but disappear you. the ones who need the message? they don't give a fuck. 
does it matter to you? it should. and remember. abuse is not gender-specific. 
and don't you dare make my post about your agenda.

text: "do you want to be made well?" jesus asked the lame man." do you want the responsibility that comes with wholeness? do you want a new identity, no longer as a victim but one of a son? healing is transformational. in the midst of such a politically charged and sometimes triggering week i think that we have¬† believed the lie that it is somehow noble to be a victim. we have congregated to the pool of brokenness to affirm our hurt rather than our healer. jesus does not wallow in our misery, he heals our brokenness and commands us to walk.¬† why do we worship our pain more than our healer? dont get me wrong, i am appalled by the abhorrent injustices wreaking havoc on our nation. but as followers of christ we have a responsibility and a calling to place our identity in our name rather than our issue. you may have been victimized but in christ, you are no victim. carry that which has been carrying you. pick up your mat so you can hold it before a generation and show the healing power of christ. let brokenness stop with you, for what the enemy meant for evil, the lord has intended for good. #metoo

text: it's weird because both nicole's i know irl and online said eerily similiar things i feel about participating in the domestic abuse blackout, not that it didn't mean anything to them but that they didn't understand how that was supposed to help, i definitely can appreciate that and need everyone to see this, know this, recognize if you're doing it or have done it or are having it done to you or if it's happening to someone you know, get help. i wish that we could take back the metoo movement and stand together about something we so often stand alone and silently thinking we've endured. for me, metoo has been too many voices sharing their stories competing for the spotlight to be heard, i want them to not have to have a spotlight then because it's terrifying and the real reason women don't report but please, let's spotlight this, when you see marks on someone and they aren't talking about it, spotlight that and maybe save a life #metoo #domesticabuse #domesticviolence #sexualassault #report

text:
an open letter of love and solidarity to my fellow womxn, survivors, friends.

if you speak up, or don‚Äôt, or cannot or have not yet. 
if you scream it in the streets covered in war paint and run to the ends of the earth until you are heard.
if you sit in silence, draw the curtains, dive in to self care and keep things close to your chest because that is the only way to feel safe right now.
if you write and paint and sing and heart it all out in prose or canvas or photo or memoir or lyric.
if you share your pain over tea and tears with another bleeding heart that quietly understands.
if you do all of this, or none at all.
however you choose to, and are able to move through your own life and the things you have endured- 
you. are. doing. it. right. 
you are doing what you need to survive and heal and move forward through battles you did not ever ask or deserve to fight.
you made it through, stronger than those who tried to drown your fire. 
because you are here.
that is the greatest victory.
and nobody has the right to shame or question or attack you for how you have moved through the battlefield.
ever.
so please don‚Äôt question yourself, either.
love yourself, for making it here, today. 
i sure do love you, too.
üñ§
#ibelieveher #ibelieveyou #metoo #fuckthepatriarchy

text:
"on my podcast, i talk to women i‚Äôve hooked up with about sex, dating, and why we didn‚Äôt work out. i do a pre-interview before i record. so this one woman says, ‚Äúi want to talk about that night.‚Äù before i hit record, i look back and she is in tears. i‚Äôm like, ‚Äútime out. what‚Äôs going on?‚Äù she tells me and i say, ‚Äúdo you mind if we get this on my podcast?‚Äù i hit record and say, ‚Äúwhy are you so emotional right now?‚Äù we had hooked up 2.5 years prior and she says, ‚Äúi thought i raped you that night. i used to think men couldn‚Äôt be raped by women. then i dated a guy who had been. i saw all the trauma he faced from that and i remembered our night together, how you brought me home, and said you didn‚Äôt want to have sex that night. i‚Äôve thought all this time i raped you.‚Äù i was like, ‚Äúhoney, no. i begrudgingly consented. i wasn‚Äôt enthusiastic about it, but i did it. you did not rape me,‚Äù and told her the story of when a woman did.
-

text:
on monday, i found the cutest picture to post, and i wanted to talk about a new thing i am incorporating in my life. then i looked at the news. this week has been incredibly challenging for me, and from what i am reading, i am not alone. as much as i would like to keep this page positive, i feel the need to address the fact that not only do i feel like i am suffering,  but also there are a large number of people who feel suffering as well. in order to better understand, i took some time this week to reread the teachings of watts and tolle, and i have come to the conclusion that i do not need to know why the suffering is happening. it is my job to allow the suffering, be with the suffering, and trust that the suffering will help my spirit to unfold and become more full. one thing that all the philosophers (past and present) agree on is spiritual growth is most abundant during periods of distress and suffering. this very dark time in our nation will be followed by abundant spiritual growth. if you are hurting because you are reliving past traumas, you are not alone. the bottom line is we are suffering, we are experiencing growing pains which are temporary. love your self in any way you can. be kind to yourself. while you are suffering, you may behave in ways that are out of character. that is ok. you just need to love yourself, and know that you are loved. you are one of many who is trying to stay sane and grow. i have been taking the time to participate in activities that bring me joy. if i need time to cry or actually just feel the suffering, then i designate time to honor that need. we have lived through some horrible events in our journeys, but i have good news for you. we have made it through 100% of the bad things that have happened to us, and we will make it through this as well. just think of how miraculous humanity will be after such a large growth spurt!! i hope this helps.
.
.
.

text:
i woke this morning exhausted. emotionally and physically spent. i sat in church with a headache that brought me to tears. frustrated that i could not be fully present. i began shaming myself for working too many hours, too many jobs, too many yeses, my village being moms to my kids, a husband out of town another weekend coaching. too often i let shame tell my narrative. 
and then i was reminded, my body was holding it all, telling my story. i didn't need shame to speak, i just needed to listen. this week was so freaking hard. my muscles and bones are just weeping. worn from carrying it all. when you have been sexually assaulted and abused, it never leaves you. it is woven into the core of your soul. this week wounds were reopened and exposed. acts of bravery were shown as women and men told their painful truth. walking into an authentic vulnerability with the hope that their story would help someone believe. that perhaps by showing their trauma, connection and empathy would be birthed. 
while perhaps some was. 
more than anything i saw and felt- silence.
leaders of churches stayed silent. aligning themselves again with a political party rather than healing. defending a man in power rather than victims weeping for mercy. they showed us who they really are. 
my heart is broken today and my body is telling me to feel it. to enter into the suffering of others is not weakness or denial that god is in control.  it is an act of the jesus i love. 
churches that spoke out today. i see you and hear you, thank you. you are the family we have been aching for. 
#yearofhope #yearofhealing #cola #golfinches #metoo #believesurvivors #yearofhope #hopewriters

text:
u n s i l e n c e d .
.
.
.
"can i be this naked with you? 
is my body safe or a safe place to be? 
will you respect me? or rape me?
am i too much to be deemed worthy of love, kindness, the most basic human needs? will you smell the scent of sex that drips from me, that which i love, that which is the way i worship and vilify me for it? will you deem me a slut, a whore? will you say ‚Äúi deserved it‚Äù or that ‚Äúi asked for it‚Äù blaming me for what he did? will you call me a ‚Äúvictim‚Äù? see me as broken because of the trauma? .
.
.
can you handle this much tenderness, that in me which demands you feel? can you feel it? can you feel me? are you willing to lay your heart bare to the fires of what must be looked at while the patriarchy is dying? or will you try once more to silence me? oh you can try, but i‚Äôll still be here writing the body erotic, dripping with sutras of sex and love. i am speaking as the voice of that which you came from, those feminine fires from which you are born. .
.
.
see you‚Äôve burned me, hung me, buried me, tried to hide me away. you‚Äôve done this to millions of us for centuries, but now it is time. .
.
.
time for the women to rise. time for the boys clubs to die and for men to truly be born. time for eros to be worshipped again. time for the holy heart to be opened wide. time for us all to come back to know these bodies of love. and time for right relationship to thrive. it is time. it is time. it is time. .
.
.
woke up with a fire in my belly, heart, and womb today after a night of deliciously cracking hearts open in a journey to love. i woke up with messages from other women asking me to ‚Äúblack out‚Äù or ‚Äúwhite out‚Äù my profile picture - to show men what a world without women would look like. it was a deep no for me to do this. with all the love and respect for however women and survivors are processing today i listened to what my feminine was calling for. instead the goddess calles me to be seen. to be naked. to be raw. to be here. i spent so many years hiding after my assault, turning down my sexuality, being smaller, avoiding men and the world. and that is not the way i choose to live now." words by caity flanagan

text:
in light of recent events...my new piece titled filter has changed. whether true or not, the recent senate judiciary hearings bring to mind how we as people deal with sexual assault and have reminded many victims of their own assault. often times, sexual assault victims don‚Äôt speak up, and they keep their attack to themselves, they filter their attack. the #metoo movement has helped be a voice for victims in the past year or so, but for the most part, victims are quiet.
.
verbal assaults are sometimes the precursor to sexual assaults, hence the triggering phrase, ‚Äúhey sweetie you should smile more!‚Äù
.
in conjunction with my piece i also have a questionnaire and of course #unsweet keychains to those who visit.
.
whether the allegations are true or not, it‚Äôs important to always be as sensitive as possible. most victims never come forward. .
my piece is a cast of my dust mask that i wear while i work on my sculptures. it is made out of hard candy mix i made myself with a spray painted clear lacquer over top to give it the shine.
.
please come check out the sculpture show in the burroughs wellcome gallery in the leo jenkins fine arts center. #feminist #femmeart #sculpture #feminism

text:
the energy of my world has been vastly different in the last few days. i have always been one to process my feelings slowly. death... trauma... triggers... anger... even sometimes love. transparency is not easy. vulnerability is not easy. while courage is present, everyone has a story to tell in their own time. my actions in the last few days may seem erratic or desperate to those closer to me, instead they are based off of me processing. this morning i woke up realizing just how much recent events have truly reflected on my energy.  i am confused. i am hurt. i am angry.... and i may not be ready to share my story but i will not be quiet. i will not apologize. i‚Äôm growing and moving forward, but there are people in this world who will never understand that. i am hurt, and as a woman i have the right to be. i am angry, and as a woman i have the right to be. but i am not my trauma or my pain. i am magical. i am beautiful. i am me despite evil. i am grateful to be alive. i am blessed to share the myself with the world on my terms. i am lucky to have people around me who both lift me up and care for me. i am powerful even if there are those in this world who tried to take my power from me. for the women who feel like their power has been stripped from them, or for those paralyzed in fear like i have been... i am bursting to send you love, i am growing despite it all to send you love.i am here. i am not quiet. i am on your side. i am on your side. i believe you. üéµ: if tonight is my last- laura izibor

text:
twice this week i took my tender heart to the ocean. .

the weight of the week.
the trauma it has triggered.
the tears i have shed.
the feelings of powerlessness and outrage.
it's all been too much.
.

let's be tender with our hearts - with each other. 
i am giving myself permission to spend as much time as i need tending to cultivating safety and compassion for my nervous system.
if you too are triggered, i hope you do too ‚ù§

text: art by @drawnbymary ‚Ä¢ words by @magamamas ‚Ä¢ ‚Äúresist the dire urgency narratives. this hearing is not the beginning or ending of anything. it is a historical moment in a wide deep vast space of many. root yourself in your goodness, your okayness, so that you can see the badness (inner and outer) without being consumed by it. the urgency will bring you down and is part of the trauma; it will render you inoperative. this is not the most grievous injustice there has ever been. kavanagh‚Äôs politics and interpretation of the constitution were problematic before any allegations arose. they were misogynistic and worthy of revolt. revealing yourself is a nuanced choice- not compulsory for healing or support. stay out of the trauma pit. are we seeing the underbelly more clearly than we have before? some of us may be. be the spark and smoldering flame. dig your heels in. listen with discernment. avoid narrative conflation. do what you need to, to feel safe. then decide if there is an action to take. do at least one thing that is truly, simply pleasurable. many people have written to ask me how to talk to their children about boundaries and consent. boundaries are happening all the time- what is your relationship to limits? do you understate them? do you allow yourself to be steamrolled? do you steamroll? do you hedge? are you afraid of pushback? do you get easily confused or disoriented? learn your own nervous system defaults and you will start to see the defaults of those around you. this is what we all need for the new normal of respect, honor and better relationships and sex for everyone. join me tuesday üêÜ lead-in. free class, @magamamas linktree has details. #traumaandtranscendence‚Äù ‚Ä¢ these words and this image helped me remember to soften. to sit in my own okayness. to stay out of the trauma pit, to practice self care, to find pleasure, and then to act. sending big love to all of you today. ‚ô•Ô∏è‚úäüèº‚ô•Ô∏èü§≤üèº‚ô•Ô∏è

text:
the first time i was sexually assaulted i was 16, working in a 5 star restaurant when one of the bus boys shoved his hand up my skirt as i walked by and tried to stick his fingers past my underwear to my vagina. after i told our manager he was immediately fired, his parents came in to apologize and find out if i was going to report their son to the police, he was a student at brother rice high school and they didn‚Äôt want his chances at college to be affected, i still regret not reporting, his name is mario. the second time i was a little older, 21, with friends after work. i had been on a few dates with an older man and suddenly he ripped my shirt low enough to expose my breast to the rest of the group, i quickly covered up, not sure why or how this had just happened, he was drunk and had never acted that way before, i still regret my lack of action, his name is steve and he never apologized and i doubt he even remembers because he was so drunk.  the third time it was my boss‚Äôs silent partner in a restaurant, he groped me and told me i‚Äôd be fired if i didn‚Äôt have an affair with him. i was fortunate enough to get away, and i told the owner, who was not at all surprised. i did not tell the police and i still regret it, his name is terry.  i am not afraid. my body is my body, and since these instances i have learned to speak up, to protect myself, and have spent hundreds and hundreds of hours in schools teaching children how to keep themselves safe from sexual predators. in my hundreds of experiences performing a play for elementary students across michigan to teach them the ‚Äúno, go, tell method‚Äù and what it means to have a ‚Äúbad‚Äù touch or a ‚Äúconfusing‚Äù touch and that they have a voice has been the hardest; i have never once performed this show without a child coming forward to get help and admit to sexual abuse or molestation. this is a bigger problem!!! if we, as people, do not stand up and use our voices who is going to teach them to use theirs?!? i‚Äôll be rewriting and updating this show and sending my request to perform it in every elementary school in our state, because i have a voice and i‚Äôm going to use it. 
#ibelievechristineblaseyford

she realized that she could no longer carry the weight of other people‚Äôs expectation or the responsibility for their happiness.

she knew that it would take work to free herself from memory but she picked up her pen as a sword and wrote a new story for herself anyway. 
she is at a place in her life where peace is her priority and negativity is just seen as an opportunity to learn just how to do that. 
this is my story and the next chapter includes you if you are willing.

text:
there are many women blacking out their profile picture today in an effort for men to see what life would be like without women. i am intentionally choosing not to participate. why?

i do not want to be invisible again. ever. i have worked hard to get to the place where i am. i will not give that up, even for a day.

i don‚Äôt believe we, as women, should be invisible, even for one day. especially to men. the culture of our country is one where a woman‚Äôs purpose is perceived to be secondary to a man‚Äôs...especially when it comes to our bodies. 
and, really, a black box does not give men an idea of what a world would be like without women. nor does it change anything. to change things, you need to be visible. tell your story. call your representatives. get involved with girls in your community. vote. 
i believe it is important to be seen and heard. therefore, my profile picture stays me and i continue to express my thoughts.  #noblackout #beheard #vote #metoo #whyididntreport

text_retweet:
#repost @ttt_official (@get_repost)
„Éª„Éª„Éª
dear women who were silenced,

this is a problematic letter. problematic because it's both an apology and a rally cry. problematic because in this society it's always innocent until proven guilty, unless the accused is a woman demanding justice. because what you've been through, is something most woman have been through at least once in their life, no matter how powerful, rich or famous.

this is a problematic letter because the world keeps telling you to raise your voice, but then stifles you the moment you open your mouth. because the society will call you an attention whore every time you call them out on their pervertedness. because when a man molests a woman, it becomes the woman's responsibility to prove her claim instead of the man's responsibility to defend his innocence.

this is a problematic letter because a man is either too young for his career to be ruined or too old for his reputation to be soiled. if he's rich she's a gold digger, if he's famous she's a power hungry bitch, if he's influential she's just crying wolf, if he's neither she's just another vengeful feminist. this is a problematic letter because there's no justice, worse still, there's no trial. it's all a matter of inconvenience which shall either be forgotten or denied, never given the importance it deserves.

this is a problematic letter, because despite all of it, you've persevered. despite the threats you haven't shrunk away from demanding the truth come out. despite the indifference you've not lost all hope.

this is a problematic letter, but it is also one to remind you, don't stop asking for justice because the world will never stop asking for anything less from you. this is to remind you that your voice might be the one which opens a floodgate of fearlessness. this is to tell you to keep your voice raised, and promise you it'll never be alone in this fight.
.
~ nilesh mondal (@hungover.hamlet)

text: this was a hard week that brought many painful memories back to the surface. it's bad enough reliving your own trauma, as survivors do from time to time, but it's even worse to watch a whole country reliving theirs and one another's at the same time. fortunately, though, it's been a weekend packed with plans with funny, smart, gorgeous women that have kept drawing me back to the here and now, the parts of the present that are more than alright. @hotel_modera invited me for a little staycation downtown, including a much-needed outdoor yoga class taught by meagan and clarissa from @revivewell_training. there was my neighbor @mylifelessordinary's party to celebrate the fabulous @pinmeuppdx community. and last night @tayloroo and i saw @thelmaandthesleaze and @shonenknifeofficial at @dantesportland. even when the big picture seems as vast and dark as the night sky, i am thankful for all the bright stars that are glowing out there, lighting the way.

text:
an invitation went out today on fb to make our profile pictures black. to illustrate what life would be like without women.

solidarity matters. together we are better. unified our strength is magnified.

and yet, to this invitation to blacken our profiles i say, that it has been too long that women have lived in the shadows. relegated to the dark corners of life and society. asked to dim our light, hide our gifts or had these forcefully taken from us. our bodies, minds, spirits -- our great mother earth -- raped by those who would extract what they want and leave us to deal. or die.

no. i will not hide my light. nor the full spectrum beauty of being. i will not keep dark, dirty secrets hidden behind a mask of shame, nor skirt the truth to keep things comfortable anymore. 
it is only when we step into the light and claim our rite to live, thrive, and co-create safely and peacefully will we enjoy harmony of being and peace in earth.

rainbow is the knew black. 
and we're bringing it back. fully. greatfully.

this day, every day, let us commit to full spectrum revelations of truth, beauty, justice, love and harmony amongst all beings.

humanity needs more empathy and love. more understanding. 
i will soon post more and more about sexual assault because i feel it's such an important issue all around the world. 
sorry for ranting i just needed to let it all out, thanks for reading everything if you have. ~üêæ -

text:
i‚Äôve been struggling to find words to publicly acknowledge what i have witnessed in the news regarding the injustices & crimes that are being committed against women. its been hard to try & articulate the array of emotions that ive felt these last couple of days as a woman...as a survivor...as an advocate...as a human being. i have prayed about this extensively, and just couldnt come up with anything that i felt was worth sharing, until today, sept 30, the eve of domestic violence awareness month. as usual, god, i see you. i got a text limit (thx instagram) so let me get straight to the point.
to all of the survivors out there: i am so sorry that happened to you, it was not your fault. i hear you. i am with you. i believe you.
to the survivors who have spoke out during this time of political uproar, thank u for being brave. your truth is culture-changing.
to the survivors who have chosen not to speak out, you are brave. you are just as important. you matter.
to the survivors who cant bear to turn their tvs on right now in fear that what they see will trigger a painful memory, your pain is real and it is valid.
to all of the men out there: we need your help. we know that the majority of u are good. we know that most of you will honor and respect women. but that is not enough anymore. we need your influence & voice. we need u to speak out against this culture that has evolved into building men up, by bringing women down. this is learned behavior, & its not your fault, but we need you part of the solution. this is not an indictment on manhood, this is an invitation. join us.
to everyone reading this: the lack of empathy in this country and in this culture is debilitating to us as a society, and as human beings. we have created a world for survivors of sa and dv to live in shame, fear of repercussions, and disbelief. instead of putting ourselves in that persons situation and trying to comprehend the horror & trauma that they have endured, we instead blame them for the circumstances that they absolutely could not control. we need to be better people.
for the month of the october, i challenge u to become the empathetic change we need in this world. (cont in comments)

text: so with all this #political stuff going on with this judge being accused of sexually assaulting a woman 30+ years ago, i thought i‚Äôd share a vague story. i was sexually assaulted in middle school, never told anyone, until one night my mom got a bad feeling. my mom found out, and has been my best friend since, because i won‚Äôt talk about it. i can tell her anything and everything. i told a few people when it was happening, but it was kept to a very small number of people. and it‚Äôs only been recently that i‚Äôve been able to talk about it (again only with certain people i trust) i may not agree about waiting so long to come forward, but who am i to judge? i never got the courage to come forward to face that person. and there‚Äôs so many women who don‚Äôt, so while i may disagree with when she did it, i‚Äôm glad she came forward. and if she‚Äôs lying i hope that it is handled properly and if she‚Äôs not lying i hope justice is given #courage #metoo #story #love #mom #justice #survivor

let us remember: not all survivors of rape and sexual assault are women! there are survivors of all genders, races, ages and abilities. as many of you know, i am survivor. there are some days when i don‚Äôt really think about it at all, and other days when i think about it constantly. i always think that i am no longer emotionally attached to my trauma, until something like this happens and a survivor‚Äôs validity and credibility are put into question (pretty much strictly by people who have never experienced it). then everything comes flooding back. sexual assault doesn‚Äôt just exist in that moment, it lives alongside you for the rest of your life. it impacts your mental and physical health, your friendships, familial bonds and romantic relationships. when you defend brett kavanaugh and call dr. blasey ford a liar, you‚Äôre not simply voicing an opinion. you are hurting all of us in a very direct way. accusations like these are in immediate correlation with why so many assaults go unreported. because we are afraid for our safety, because we are afraid of police, because we are afraid nothing will be done, because we are afraid people won‚Äôt believe us. and in our current climate, belief is no longer enough. we need your support, because with momentum, we can make big changes. (note: i made this drawing). #believesurvivors #ibelieveher #ibelievethem #reasonstobelieve #ibelievechristineblaseyford #timesupnow #metoo #raiseyourvoice

text:
start changing the conversations my brothers!

the underlying expectation seems to be that men have to be strong, and that showing emotion is incompatible with that strength. 
yet, showing anger is acceptable, and is framed as an exception to the rule or as not an emotion at all. this is toxic.
.
relatedly, the idea that a real man cannot be a victim of abuse, or that talking about it is shameful, is a toxic part of our culture that needs to be changed.
.
as a male who has been a victim of both sexual and non sexual abuse, i can personally tell you there is nothing wrong with admitting it to yourself or those close to you. a lot of the shame that we feel we place on ourselves first. it‚Äôs okay to not be okay, let‚Äôs stop the shame, and start reshaping our culture and language surrounding consent and sexuality on all spectrums. üíõ
.
.
.
.

text:
here‚Äôs the thing. i had a slew of amazing women reach out to me via pm telling me about the female blackout today, and usually i don‚Äôt participate in these types of things but i figured i would try it on for size and see how it felt.

when i changed my profile image to black, it didn‚Äôt feel good to me. in the face of everything that‚Äôs happening in the world, i don‚Äôt want to disappear to prove my significance. it feels counter-intuitive to what we are trying to accomplish. 
i want to show up as i do everyday, continuing to embody all that i believe and stand for in the world in my joy, in my passion, in my truth, in my light.

when i think about it, blacking out my image feels similar to withholding my love in order to manipulate for someone‚Äôs attention and affection. and what winds up happening in that scenario is i just end up feeling lonely and resentful. we need a more direct and connected approach to change.

so i‚Äôm glad i tried it, and i love the intention of creating solidarity amongst woman to bring about positive change in this world. may this post invite each of us to explore what our own unique form of activism is, because mine certainly may be different from yours.

i am here as a voice, i am here as a channel, i am here as a catalyst for collective wake-up and transformation, and i, am not going anywhere.

#rememberwhoyouare
#theappetitecourse #womentogether #trustyourself #riseup #divinefeminine #magicisreal #metoo #metoomovement #sovereignrelating #intimacybydesign

when i changed my profile image to black, it didn‚Äôt feel good to me. in the face of everything that‚Äôs happening in the world, i don‚Äôt want to disappear to prove my significance. it feels counter-intuitive to what we are trying to accomplish. 
i want to show up as i do everyday, continuing to embody all that i believe and stand for in the world in my joy, in my passion, in my truth, in my light.

when i think about it, blacking out my image feels similar to withholding my love in order to manipulate for someone‚Äôs attention and affection. and what winds up happening in that scenario is i just end up feeling lonely and resentful. we need a more direct and connected approach to change.

text:
the #struggle is real.

as an aspie i have been masking my entire life, just so that i can be part of the crowd. i used to see people enjoy their time and i wanted that too.
sadly it doesnt always work like that and its not easy at all. in the process i guess i lost myself.

now with the diagnosis i am trying hard to be me and be honest with what i am and how things should be. its not easy now as well as people are unable to understand.

i just wanted to be accepted. just wanted to be liked, picked up for teams, to have friends, enjoy life.

its not easy.

i do not care if it is only an hour. i do not care if you think i am disregarding some pact. this is not a time for silence.
.
it has actually never been a time for silence. yet, that is what the majority of white people do. stay silent in the face of the abuse, assault, and dehumanizing of  bipoc folx.
.
our silence and complicity is why what‚Äôs his face was elected. it‚Äôs why the other one was nominated to the supreme court. it‚Äôs why white women would rather take crumbs from men than use their voices and power. it‚Äôs why we (white people) have our own internalized misogyny we have to unpack and face.
.
so, we are having to look what our country is all about square in the eyes - because your silence has not protected you.
.
this is a collective issue that we must address and be willing to be uncomfortable with, wade through the mud, and see what‚Äôs on the other side.
.
there will always be more freedom in that than in staying locked in the silence.
.
.
.
.

text:
men ask why women are so pissed off. even guys with wives and daughters. jackson katz, a prominent social researcher, illustrates why.  he's done it with hundreds of audiences: "i draw a line down the middle of a chalkboard, sketching a male symbol on one side and a female symbol on the other.
then i ask just the men: what steps do you guys take, on a daily basis, to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? at first there is a kind of awkward silence as the men try to figure out if they've been asked a trick question. the silence gives way to a smattering of nervous laughter. occasionally, a young a guy will raise his hand and say, 'i stay out of prison.' this is typically followed by another moment of laughter, before someone finally raises his hand and soberly states, 'nothing. i don't think about it.'
then i ask the women the same question. what steps do you take on a daily basis to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? women throughout the audience immediately start raising their hands. as the men sit in stunned silence, the women recount safety precautions they take as part of their daily routine.
hold my keys as a potential weapon. look in the back seat of the car before getting in. carry a cell phone. don't go jogging at night. lock all the windows when i sleep, even on hot summer nights. be careful not to drink too much. don't put my drink down and come back to it; make sure i see it being poured. own a big dog. carry mace or pepper spray. have an unlisted phone number. have a man's voice on my answering machine. park in well-lit areas. don't use parking garages. don't get on elevators with only one man, or with a group of men. vary my route home from work. watch what i wear. don't use highway rest areas. use a home alarm system. don't wear headphones when jogging. avoid forests or wooded areas, even in the daytime. don't take a first-floor apartment. go out in groups. own a firearm. meet men on first dates in public places. make sure to have a car or cab fare. don't make eye contact with men on the street. make assertive eye contact with men on the street.‚Äù #notpolitical #lifeordeath 
#menvswomen #metoo #thatswhy

text:
behind the scenes on the @portermagazine #edit shoot by @carlota_guerrero with @modelactivist .
.
.
#modelmafia has made me proud to say i'm a model. i used to be embarrased when i said what i do. now, i can truly say i'm proud to be a model because we stand for something more than a cute selfie. as a collective we are using our individual voices to make real change in the industry and world at large. üëä
for me personally, the most inspiring activations we did was to bring the #metoo movement to the fashion industry. as a victim of sexual assualt and harrassement myself, i was connected by the group to press and given the opportunity to share my story anonymously with the world on social media as well as with @thekitca 
this was a hugely freeing experience for me. üó£
we started the ball rolling a couple years ago with a models only safe-space discussion. i knew this would be something special from the start. every woman on the panel had a profound personal story about modeling that i could deeply relate to. prior to this meeting i had never experienced a sense of community with other models. üíõ
that is why this shoot was such a major milestone; to show the community and genuine respect and love we all have developed for one another. üèÅ
.

text:
last night i had a dream that i was being harassed and assaulted. thank goodness it was only a dream in this particular situation. it started with me saying ‚Äúplease stop‚Äù and ‚Äúplease go away‚Äù to the assaulter while people on the street kept walking. i asked for help and the response was looking away or saying ‚Äúwhat do you expect me to do?‚Äù the dream evolved into my body being drug across concrete by pulling my hands to an unknown destination for unknown reasons with my assaulter laughing. it wasn‚Äôt until i was crying and screaming that somebody helped me get released and the helper said, ‚Äúthere was nothing i could do until i knew he was actually hurting you.‚Äù while i am no stranger to bad dreams on a regular basis, i think that it‚Äôs clear that the #metoo movement certainly inspired the dream. the worst part of the dream was not the assaulter, but all of those people that could have helped from the beginning but chose not to. 
unfortunately, this reaction is one i seem to see often by those unaffected or not oppressed. just because it didn‚Äôt happen to you, it doesn‚Äôt mean it doesn‚Äôt happen. just because you didn‚Äôt see it, it doesn‚Äôt mean it didn‚Äôt happen. and this applies to much more situations of injustice beyond the me too movement. #beagoodhuman #bethepersonyourdogthinksyouare #fightforsomethingbetter

text:
my feed has been flooded with so many posts that have triggered me, enraged me, made me laugh, made me cry, made me want to burn everything to the ground.  this is why i make art.  this is why my art is ‚Äútoo emotional‚Äù, ‚Äútoo theatrical‚Äù, ‚Äútoo dark‚Äù. i‚Äôm done with defending my work against the same criticisms that are hurled at women over and over again.  i‚Äôve been silenced too long throughout my life that words very often fail me.  so, i use my voice in my art.  i rage, i scream, i sob, and i speak as much as i can through my sculpture because we must be heard. 
#ibelieveher  #whyididntreport #neverthelessshepersisted #metoo  #art #artistsoninstagram

text:
"that i can tell you that it took me years to process all the harm done to me between the ages of 17 and 23‚Ä¶.. i‚Äôm still processing. 
i don‚Äôt want to recount my assaults to validate my story anymore. 
does everyone need to know my stories so that they can decide for themselves if they feel pity? 
to determine if i‚Äôm a liar? 
what is this desire for trauma porn? 
do you feel empowered yet? 
am i a victim or a survivor now? 
and why am i only offered these two options."
‚ùÑ
this week for #sundaysentiments @queerfutures_ is clearly in response to the media being saturated with discussions on rape and sexual assault, full of #metoo stories, and full with a sense of pressure for myself to feel empowered or supported by all of it. 
i wanted to sit with the discomfort i have been feeling towards using the terms victim and survivor for myself in relation to both being raped and domestically abused. because they have always felt restricting or like i am meant to be able to feel a connection with everyone else using them. they have felt like too much expectation or too much of a statement in relation to where i am at in healing from this trauma and pain.
‚ùÑ

text:
i‚Äôm not one to wade into political debates or the like. but as the world awaits with bated breath about the ruling on #brettkavanaugh and his possible ascension to the us supreme court, i feel compelled to share my 2 cents worth. on this topic and the wider topic of gender inequality, gender based-violence and ultimately sexual harassment/assault. 
as the #metoo movement has shown, for too long there‚Äôs been a quiet acceptance that men in powerful positions have  the monopoly on truth. this has perpetuated a culture of ‚Äòwell she was asking for it‚Äô. i like every woman have no doubt experienced this. this being everything from; micro-aggressions, cat-calling, harassment and in the worst cases assault. it is unacceptable and inexcusable to standby and condone this behaviour. a person should be free and safe from predation. i have been giving particular thought to this over the past week. in this 21st century it shouldn‚Äôt be this hard to understand women‚Äôs rights and our demand for equal dignity. i mean come on... is it really that hard to understand and accept that a woman deserves equal treatment and respect in the workplace and beyond? 
to the #harveyweinstein ‚Äòs of the world - your time is over. to the brave women of the world - your time is now. 
and to those who remain undecided, i urge you to be cognisant of by-stander participation. if you do nothing to help change the culture of sexism in our world, then you remain complicit in the institutional and engrained misogyny that has taken so many victims. 
whatever comes of the investigation please know that this is an unprecedented moment in the us and the history of the world. a decision either way will alter the narrative of an entire country and either change culture or further and more deeply embed it. i know which side i‚Äôm on, do you? 
despite the darkness that surrounds this, the mere fact that so many brave women have come forward to share their testimonies and stand against gender-based violence and harassment is nothing short of an act of true heroin-ism. 
i salute you and i stand with you my sisters. & know that you should never apologise for being such powerful women.

text: what a week. i finally got over a virus-induced migraine that lasted for three completely debilitating days, while feeling turned upside down and inside out by the kavanaugh fiasco. i have so many emotions and so many old and painful memories have surfaced - things that i never fully dealt with. as a  recent @nytimes article noted, the senate vote after the weeklong (üôÑ) fbi investigation will demonstrate the power or limits of the #metoo movement. regardless of the outcome, the movement is certainly gaining more power at social levels. hoping that as more women come forward, men also do - demonstrating compassion, commiseration, and even reaching out and apologizing to those that they may have hurt in the past. we all have skeletons in our closets. do the right thing and take responsibility for your past actions and maybe we can find forgives and reconciliation. #believesurvivors #backbend #ustrasana #camelpose #yogahealing #homepractice #yogalove #myyogajourney #ibelieveher

text:
yesterday i attended the @glblctzn festival in central park. global citizen is a movement of engaged citizens who are using their collective voice to end extreme poverty by 2030. 
______
in between performances, there were many speakers that highlighted the efforts they are making to bring awareness to domestic/physical/verbal abuse to women, the importance of voting, providing education to children education in rural parts of the world, providing healthcare including a hiv vaccine and protecting our environment, oceans, ecosystems. global citizens can learn about the systemic causes of extreme poverty, take action on those issues, and earn rewards for their actions ‚Äî as part of a global community committed to lasting change. 
_____
the united nations general assembly started last week and many world leaders were at the concert to speak about these initiatives. my heart feels a little hopeful, despite last weeks hearing here in the us, we are just a tiny nation in this world and there are so many people who are literally dying for a meal to eat, a school to go to, and water to shower. cardi b said last night- america does not know extreme poverty and she is so right. i posted some clips from last night, but i believe the whole concert is probably on youtube. 
____
be inspired.

text:
just last night on my way to get pizza, i stopped to get gas and while at the pump i had my keys in my hand... no biggie where else would i have them. it wasn‚Äôt just that they were in my hand it was the way they were in my hand. my thumb was on the panic button and the other keys were between my individual fingers something akin to brass knuckles. i have no conscious memory of arranging them so. i only noticed once i was in my vehicle and had to put my key in the ignition. 
i don‚Äôt remember feeling particularly unsafe while pumping gas. it‚Äôs just soo ingrained to be that hyper vigilant that as a woman at night alone it‚Äôs as natural as breathing. what i do remember while i was pumping my gas and constantly looking around me, was noticing the lone gas attendant, a young girl, working by herself and a man, a customer who kept going in and out of the gas station, he didn‚Äôt look particularly threatening. however i watched the scene play out and particularly the young lady‚Äôs body language towards the customer to make sure she was okay. 
now i‚Äôve never experienced firsthand extreme violence or aggression but i have experienced the subtle and not so subtle negative attention from some males. i say some males because i‚Äôve had the privilege of being surrounded by good men who have always had the women in their lives back and have always treated those women with care and respect. 
this is the reality for most if not all women. many of us don‚Äôt even realize we do these safety checks or are that hyper aware it has become so ingrained in our very fibre. #stopviolenceagainstwomen #secondnature #metoo

text: i have been very disturbed this week, as i have seen the tanushree datta, christine blasey ford and brett kavanaugh episodes unfold. i am shocked that most men all over the world are so scared of women now, that they are ganging up like this against them. i do think due justice should be served after an investigation in both cases, but i do think women are very strong to speak up, how many ever years later. i look back now and think all of the times i have been even slightly sexually molested: the time i got groped by 6 men as i made my way down to the front of a dtc bus in delhi, to getting a finger inside my ass in a crowded alley of sarojini nagar, to having my skirt picked up by a man on a scooter who said he was an uncle who just wanted some water as i walked to the bus stop as a 13 year old, and i cringe, and feel embarrassed and humiliated and disgusted. i never told anyone. no wonder i have shut these incidents out, as they make me feel so gross i can‚Äôt even talk about it. blacked it out, forgot, moved on with life, not realising that i am unsafe every second of every day. i don‚Äôt like talking about it cos it makes me feel dirty and powerless and the fact that women come out and talk about it is so inspiring, and we should never stop, never stop. we should talk and we should say what we have to, and you need to give us a hearing. hear us, listen to us, let us make our stand. it‚Äôs been high time coming.

text:
you never really know your parents until you become an adult. it makes sense why they punished you when you prank called 911. 
you never realize who your real friends are until you throw up the bat signal and they come by your side.

it doesn't hit you that you've been raped until the next day, next month, or maybe years later. i'm sure i'm not the only one whose timeline has been flooded with "why i didn't report". no one would believe me, they were my friend, i was drunk...they scrutinize everything. your social media, your sexual history, or your job. on one side i'm like yes! tell your story so this doesn't happen again! yell it! 
it's the reactions that hurt my heart. the accusations. the excuses. the false martyr's we create out of something they should know better. you shouldn't be afraid to be alone with a woman if you use your words. "it's embarrassing to ask for consent". i guess you're not mature enough to be having sex then huh?

text:
there are things that kill us. there are things that make us stronger. but mostly, there‚Äôs just life. days full of lessons, moments we learn there are no medals for doing the right thing. in fact, sometimes doing what your conscience calls you to do costs more than it would to slither into court in (male?) jeggings and the designer jacket your opponent bought you, not a shred of elegance or honest emotion in sight. 
speaking of which, i was in court this past week. i won‚Äôt talk about it in depth because i haven‚Äôt gotten to the other side of it yet. suffice it to say that i learned lessons. 
my attorney is up against a brilliant criminal defender who would be a joy to watch were she not working for the wrong team. at one point, she arched an eyebrow at me and said, ‚Äúyou do realize everyone in amsterdam speaks english.‚Äù it was not a question. it was a judgement. apparently, escaping a 10-hour assault, jumping into a cab and the next flight out of there, then, on his parents‚Äô advice, arriving exhausted, in pain and in tears at the hospital with my luggage and a fresh set of bruises isn‚Äôt enough. everyone in amsterdam speaks english. she knows because she‚Äôs from there. üôÑ if i had been attacked, as i claim, by the man i sincerely loved, i would surely have gone straight to the dutch police to press charges. 
lessons, yes. 
i learned i have what it takes to face this. to get up the next day, give my all in a lively presentation as part of a job i‚Äôm passionate about and continue giving of myself authentically in motherhood and in friendship and know i will walk back into that courtroom again no matter what.
.
.
.

i survived and was forced to hide thru physical, sexual, mental abuse since the age of 3. i've had years of nights pretending to sleep thru my ex changing his mind on how he was going to kill me having knives, guns, glass held to me wondering if i could fight him off or at least kill him also if he acted. years of being forced to stay quiet from childhood do to religious abuse. i will not hide my survival, determination, and strength. this is not how we heal.

#wearevisable
#repost from @theprojectpatchwork with @regram.app ... women around the world today are hiding in solidarity.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
you may have seen many accounts with profiles blacked out today between 8am and 9pm. this is a movement to raise awareness about domestic abuse and sexual assault against women and one i will not be taking part in.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i have spent years fighting to be heard, to be seen. a movement for any cause that involves hiding is not one i can participate in. i stand in plain sight in solidarity with all women, i resist the blackout but embrace the shout out and it‚Äôs message. i just do ‚Äòt believe that leaving social media or hiding from it is in any way beneficial to society. in order to raise awareness we need to be seen and heard. we have spent centuries fighting for our rights as women, to be taken seriously and respected. i too was sexually abused and i will not be silenced.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i will continue to use my voice to help women with invisible illnesses and refuse to be invisible for any cause. i hope it brings them the awareness they hoped for but wish for them to find a more visible way of raising awareness in the future so more of us can stand with them.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
did you participate?

text:
while taking a break from social media some things have happened in our political system that doesnt sit too well with me. this photo was taken about 7 days after it happened. the happiness on my face hides the pain that happened. this trip to sf was my mental breakdown- i left in the middle of a semester and went to sf. just left. and that mental anguish is still there. so excuse me- i dont doubt dr.ford. its 4 years later and i still cry. i cry because i was forced to make a decison that haunts me, that pains me. a decison i shouldnt have had to make. so in case you dont understand why women dont report/ press rape charges- let me give you my reasons : #hewasmarried #hehadakid #hewasinthearmy #idhavetogotocourt #iknewitwouldbehesaidshesaid
#hewasinabiggerpowerpositionthanme 
this happens to so many women around you but yet we dont speak up because of fear. ive been pretty open with part of what happened to me, and well honestly the other part is painful and private. so if youre asking yourself why does something that happened 36 years ago matter? then you‚Äôre also part of the problem. 
#metoo #metoomovement
